{"title_page": "Nee Pathi Naan Pathi", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Nee Pathi Naan Pathi\n| image =\n| director = [[Vasanth]]\n| producer = Rajam Balachander<br />Pushpa Kandaswamy\n| writer = [[Vasanth]]\n| starring = [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]]<br />[[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]]<br />[[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]]\n| music = [[M. M. Keeravani|Maragadha Mani]]\n| cinematography = R. Ganesh\n| editing = Ganesh Kumar\n| studio = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| released = 12 September 1991\n| runtime =\n| country = India\n| language = Tamil\n}}\n'''''Nee Pathi Naan Pathi''''' ({{lang-en|You are one half, I am one half}}) is a 1991 [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[romantic drama film]] directed by [[Vasanth]] and produced by [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]. The film stars [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]], [[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]] and [[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]] in the lead roles and second film in Tamil (after [[Azhagan]] ) for popular Telugu music composer [[M. M. Keeravani]] under the [[pseudonym]] Maragathamani. The film's title is based on a song from ''[[Keladi Kanmani]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nA young graduate (Rehman) falls in love with an illicit daughter (Gautami) of a venerated judge. The guy's father comes to know of the affair; helps his son set up a scene to introduce Gautami to their dominated mother, Manorama. Manorama likes the girl immediately and goes on to the Judge's house asking for Gautami's hand to his first wife and ends up being bashed up. The second unmarried wife comes to know of the scene and begs the judge to give a moral life to their daughter. Judge goes to meet Rehman's parents and Manorama is not convinced. Rehman's father gives him cash asking him to elope with Gautami. Meanwhile, the illicit wife gets arranged to be awarded for her acting skills from the hands of her own-not-publicly-known husband by their drama company chief played by Janarthanan. The scenes run parallel. As Gautami elopes with Rehman, the award ceremony happens and when the mother was called to be awarded, she was spotted dead not being able to accept her daughter's eloped marriage. When she was shown to fall down, the car in which the couples eloped meets with an accident. Few months pass by. The couples stay in Ooty where Heera falls in love with Rehman and that's when it is shown that Gautami has turned mentally retard after the accident. Though Rehman firmly resists the entry of Heera in his life, he is helpless in needing help to look after Gautami when he's not at home. Janarthanan happens to visit Ooty for a drama and shocked by Gautami's stage, asks Rehman to go for a booze party. Rehman comes back home not conscious. Meanwhile, on ill-health issues, Rehman takes Gautami to a doctor and while treatment, by miracle, Gautami completely recovers. When everyone around is happy, Heera gets to know of her pregnancy through Rehman. She decides to hide it. But on the day of Rehman's wedding with Gautami, Gautami gets to know.. On a conversation with Rehman, Heera and Janarthanan; Gautami decides to break the wedding against the wishes of everyone. In the end, Rehman marries Heera.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]] as Nandha\n* [[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]] as Nivedha\n* [[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]] as Madhu\n* [[Janagaraj]] as Ramasamy\n* [[Poornam Vishwanathan]]\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Vedavalli\n* [[Srividya]] as Kalpanadevi\n* [[Disco Shanthi]] as Ramasamy's wife\n* [[Jaishankar]]\n* [[Delhi Ganesh]]\n* [[Ganeshkar]]\n* [[Sulakshana (actress)|Sulakshana]]\n* [[K. S. Jayalakshmi]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\nSoundtrack is composed by Maragathamani.<ref>https://www.raaga.com/tamil/movie/Nee-Paadhi-Naan-Paadhi-songs-T0001955</ref>.  Lyrics is penned by Vaali.\n\n*Pudhiya pookalai paarthu - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n*Yaarai keattu eera kaatru poovai killum - Yesudas, Chithra\n*Paatu paatu padipathenna poonkaatru - Chithra\n*Devan theerpendrum puthiranathu - Yesudas\n*Pondatti kuppidum pothu pogatha ambala ethu - Chithra\n*Kaalam ulla varai Nee paathi - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Chithra\n*Sa Sa Sa Sani thapa niveathaa - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n==Reception==\n''The Indian Express'' praised Vasanth for his direction and content but was critical of second half of the film.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19910913&printsec=frontpage&hl=en</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Kavithalaya Productions}}\n{{Vasanth}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by M. M. Keeravani]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vasanth]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-romantic-drama-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-Tamil-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Nee Pathi Naan Pathi\n| image =\n| director = [[Vasanth]]\n| producer = Rajam Balachander<br />Pushpa Kandaswamy\n| writer = [[Vasanth]]\n| starring = [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]]<br />[[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]]<br />[[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]]\n| music = [[M. M. Keeravani|Maragadha Mani]]\n| cinematography = R. Ganesh\n| editing = Ganesh Kumar\n| studio = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| distributor = [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]\n| released = 12 September 1991\n| runtime =\n| country = India\n| language = Tamil\n}}\n'''''Nee Pathi Naan Pathi''''' ({{lang-en|You are one half, I am one half}}) is a 1991 [[Tamil language|Tamil]] [[romantic drama film]] directed by [[Vasanth]] and produced by [[Kavithalayaa Productions]]. The film stars [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]], [[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]] and [[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]] in the lead roles and second film in Tamil (after [[Azhagan]] ) for popular Telugu music composer [[M. M. Keeravani]] under the [[pseudonym]] Maragathamani. The film's title is based on a song from ''[[Keladi Kanmani]]''.\n\n==Plot==\nA young graduate (Rehman) falls in love with an illicit daughter (Gautami) of a venerated judge. The guy's father comes to know of the affair; helps his son set up a scene to introduce Gautami to their dominated mother, Manorama. Manorama likes the girl immediately and goes on to the Judge's house asking for Gautami's hand to his first wife and ends up being bashed up. The second unmarried wife comes to know of the scene and begs the judge to give a moral life to their daughter. Judge goes to meet Rehman's parents and Manorama is not convinced. Rehman's father gives him cash asking him to elope with Gautami. Meanwhile, the illicit wife gets arranged to be awarded for her acting skills from the hands of her own-not-publicly-known husband by their drama company chief played by Janarthanan. The scenes run parallel. As Gautami elopes with Rehman, the award ceremony happens and when the mother was called to be awarded, she was spotted dead not being able to accept her daughter's eloped marriage. When she was shown to fall down, the car in which the couples eloped meets with an accident. Few months pass by. The couples stay in Ooty where Heera falls in love with Rehman and that's when it is shown that Gautami has turned mentally retard after the accident. Though Rehman firmly resists the entry of Heera in his life, he is helpless in needing help to look after Gautami when he's not at home. Janarthanan happens to visit Ooty for a drama and shocked by Gautami's stage, asks Rehman to go for a booze party. Rehman comes back home not conscious. Meanwhile, on ill health issues, Rehman takes Gautami to a doctor and while treatment, by miracle, Gautami completely recovers. When everyone around is happy, Heera gets to know of her pregnancy through Rehman. She decides to hide it. But on the day of Rehman's wedding with Gautami, Gautami gets to know.. On a conversation with Rehman, Heera and Janarthanan; Gautami decides to break the wedding against the wishes of everyone. In the end, Rehman gets married to Heera.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Rahman (actor)|Rahman]] as Nandha\n* [[Gouthami Tadimalla|Gouthami]] as Nivedha\n* [[Heera Rajagopal|Heera]] as Madhu\n* [[Janagaraj]] as Ramasamy\n* [[Poornam Vishwanathan]]\n* [[Manorama (Tamil actress)|Manorama]] as Vedavalli\n* [[Srividya]] as Kalpanadevi\n* [[Disco Shanthi]] as Ramasamy's wife\n* [[Jaishankar]]\n* [[Delhi Ganesh]]\n* [[Ganeshkar]]\n* [[Sulakshana (actress)|Sulakshana]]\n*[[K. S. Jayalakshmi]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\nSoundtrack is composed by Maragathamani.<ref>https://www.raaga.com/tamil/movie/Nee-Paadhi-Naan-Paadhi-songs-T0001955</ref>.  Lyrics is penned by Vaali.\n\n*Pudhiya pookalai paarthu - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n*Yaarai keattu eera kaatru poovai killum - Yesudas, Chithra\n*Paatu paatu padipathenna poonkaatru - Chithra\n*Devan theerpendrum puthiranathu - Yesudas\n*Pondatti kuppidum pothu pogatha ambala ethu - Chithra\n*Kaalam ulla varai Nee paathi - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam, Chithra\n*Sa Sa Sa Sani thapa niveathaa - S. P. Balasubrahmanyam\n\n==Reception==\n''The Indian Express'' praised Vasanth for his direction and content but was critical of second half of the film.<ref>https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=P9oYG7HA76QC&dat=19910913&printsec=frontpage&hl=en</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Kavithalaya Productions}}\n{{Vasanth}}\n\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1991 films]]\n[[Category:1990s romantic drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by M. M. Keeravani]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vasanth]]\n[[Category:Indian romance films]]\n[[Category:1990s Tamil-language films]]\n\n\n{{1990s-romantic-drama-film-stub}}\n{{1990s-Tamil-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nee_Pathi_Naan_Pathi"}
{"title_page": "Contempt of Parliament", "text_new": "{{use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\nIn countries with a [[parliamentary system of government]], '''contempt of Parliament''' is the offence of obstructing the [[legislature]] in the carrying out of its functions, or of hindering any [[legislator]] in the performance of their duties. The concept is common in countries with a parliamentary system in the [[Westminster system|Westminster model]], or which are derived from or influenced by the Westminster model. The offence is known by various other names in jurisdictions in which the legislature is not called \"[[Parliament]]\", most notably '''[[contempt of Congress]]''' in the United States. Actions that may constitute contempt of Parliament include:\n* deliberately misleading a house of the legislature, or a legislative [[committee]];\n* refusing to [[testify]] before, or to produce documents to, a house or committee; and\n* attempting to influence a member of the legislature by bribery or threats.\n\nIn some jurisdictions, a house of the legislature may declare any act to constitute contempt, and this is not subject to judicial review. In others, contempt of Parliament is defined by [[statute]]; while the legislature makes the initial decision of whether to punish for contempt, the person or organisation in contempt may appeal to the [[court]]s. Some jurisdictions consider contempt of Parliament to be a criminal offence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.claruspress.ie/shop/contempt-of-parliament/|title=Contempt of Parliament|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\n\n===Commonwealth level===\nIn the [[Commonwealth of Australia]], the ''Parliamentary Privileges Act 1987'' defines contempt of Parliament as:\n\n{{quote|Conduct (including the use of words)... [which] amounts, or is intended or likely to amount, to an improper interference with the free exercise by a House or committee of its authority or functions, or with the free performance by a member of the member's duties as a member.}}\n\nContempt decisions by the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] or the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] are subject to review by federal courts. This follows after the [[Browne\u2013Fitzpatrick privilege case, 1955|Browne\u2013Fitzpatrick privilege case]], in which Morgan, Fitzpatrick and Frank Browne were denied legal representation, subsequently convicted, and served 90 days each in jail for publishing an allegedly defamatory article against a member of Parliament.\n\nPunishments are limited under the Act to (for individuals) a [[fine (penalty)|fine]] of $5,000 and/or six months' imprisonment, or (for corporations) a fine of $25,000.\n\nIn the Senate, allegations of contempt are heard by the Privileges Committee, which decides whether or not contempt was committed, and if so, what punishment is to be imposed. In practice, there have been very few times when a hearing determined that anyone was in contempt, and on no occasions has anyone been punished beyond a warning, with an apology and/or other appropriate remedial action.\n\n===State level===\n{{expand section|date=January 2013}}\n\n==Canada==\n\n===Federal level===\n{{See also|Censure#Canada|Parliamentary privilege#In Canada}}\n\nThe power to find a person in contempt of Parliament stemmed from Section 18 of the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]'' in which \"The privileges, immunities, and powers to be held, enjoyed&nbsp;... shall not confer any privileges, immunities, or powers exceeding those at the passing of such Act held, enjoyed, and exercised by the Commons House of Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and by the members thereof.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/en/const/2.html#anchorbo-ga:s_17|title=Constitution Acts, 1867|website=Laws.justice.gc.ca|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the above-mentioned \"privileges\" there is an important difference between the \"individual parliamentary privileges\" and \"collective parliamentary privileges\". This difference is also important in any case of \"[[breach of privilege]]\" as it applies to [[Parliamentary privilege#In Canada|parliamentary privilege in Canada]].\n\n====Contempt citation cases for individuals====\nRarely has the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian federal Parliament]] invoked its power to find an individual in contempt: There were \"contempt citation\" cases in 1913,<ref name=\"rare\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/topics/news/story.html?id=42920e1a-7f36-4dbc-902b-8b6cf9ae96bb |title=Examples of 'rare' contempt of Parliament cases |author=Canwest News Service |date=April 10, 2008 |publisher=CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc |accessdate=21 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411213208/http://www.canada.com/topics/news/story.html?id=42920e1a-7f36-4dbc-902b-8b6cf9ae96bb |archive-date=April 11, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 1976,<ref name=\"rare\"/> 2003,<ref name=\"rare\"/> 2008<ref name=\"rare\"/> and 2011.<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |title=PM on rulings: 'win some, lose some' |author= Laura Payton|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/09/pol-speaker-rulings.html |newspaper= [[CBC News]]|date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe April 10, 2008 case involved [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] deputy commissioner [[Barbara George (deputy commissioner)|Barbara George]] who was cited for contempt for deliberately misleading a [[parliamentary committee]] over an [[Giuliano Zaccardelli#Controversy over income trust file|income trust scandal]]. She was ultimately found in contempt but was not punished further than the [[Motion (legal)|motion]] itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2008/04/10/rcmp-contempt.html|title=RCMP deputy commissioner found in contempt of Parliament|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe March 2011 contempt citation case involved [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] MP [[Bev Oda]].<ref name=\"PM\"/> While she was found to be ''[[prima facie]]'' in contempt by the [[Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada|Speaker]], Oda was not formally held in contempt because Parliament was dissolved before a vote could be held on the matter.<ref name=\"hook\">{{cite news |title=Oda off the hook |author=Mike De Souza |url= https://montrealgazette.com/business/hook/4507178/story.html|newspaper= [[Montreal Gazette]]|date= March 26, 2011|accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Contempt citation cases for governments====\nOn March 9, 2011, [[Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada|Speaker]] of the [[House of Commons of Canada]] [[Peter Milliken]] made two contempt of Parliament rulings: The first found that a [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]] cabinet minister, [[Bev Oda]], could possibly be in contempt of Parliament.<ref name=\"PM\"/> The second ruling found the [[Cabinet of Canada|Cabinet]] could possibly be in contempt of Parliament for not meeting Opposition members' requests for details of proposed bills and their cost estimates, an issue which had \"been dragging on since the fall of 2010\".<ref name=\"PM\"/><ref name=\"findings\"/> Milliken ruled that both matters must go to their responsible parliamentary committees and that the committee was required to report its findings to the Speaker by March 21, 2011 \u2013 one day before the proposal of the budget.\n\nConcerning the Speaker's first ruling, on March 18, 2011, Opposition members of the committee (who outnumbered the government members) said they still judged Oda to be in contempt of Parliament, despite her testimony that day,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/03/18/pol-oda-privilege.html |title=MPs to return Monday on contempt debate |author=Laura Payton|date=18 March 2011|work= |publisher= [[CBC News]]|accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref> but the committee process never proceeded far enough to make a finding as to whether Oda was in contempt.<ref name=\"hook\"/><ref name=\"findings\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/21/pol-privilege-contempt.html |title=MPs' report finds government in contempt |author= |date=21 March 2011|work= |publisher= [[CBC News]] |accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the Speaker's second ruling, on March 21, 2011, the committee tabled a report<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/content/hoc/Committee/403/PROC/Reports/RP5047570/procrp27/procrp27-e.pdf |title=Question of Privilege Relating to the Failure of the Government To Fully Provide the Documents as Ordered by the House: Report of the Standing Committee on Procedure and House Affairs |accessdate=2011-04-26 |date=March 2011}}</ref> that found the Government of Canada in contempt of Parliament.<ref name=\"findings\"/> As such, a [[motion of no confidence]] was introduced in the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltvcalgary.com/personalities/Liberals+introduce+confidence+motion/4489986/story.html |title=Global News &#124; Latest & Current News - Weather, Sports & Health News |website=Globaltvcalgary.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-31}}</ref> On March 25, 2011, [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Members of Parliament]] voted on this motion, declaring a lack of confidence by a vote of 156 to 145 and [[2011 Canadian federal election|forcing an election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/25/pol-defeat.html |title=MPs gather for historic vote |author=[[CBC News]] |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref> The contempt finding is unique in Canadian history. In a wider context, it is the first time that any government in the 54-member [[Commonwealth of Nations]], either [[Commonwealth Realm]] or parliamentary republic, has been found in contempt of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110325/wpg_election_110325/20110325/?hub=WinnipegHome |title= Harper government topples on contempt motion, triggering May election|author= Bruce Cheadle|date=Mar 25, 2011 |work= |publisher= [[The Canadian Press]]; [[CTV news]]|accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Walkom: Yes, contempt of Parliament does matter |author= Thomas Walkom|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/962022--walkom-yes-contempt-of-parliament-does-matter |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=March 25, 2011 |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nEarlier that week, all three opposition parties had indicated that they would oppose the government's budget, with the NDP saying that the Conservatives' concessions did not go far enough, and the Bloc's earlier demands for $5 billion to their home province (including compensation for the 1998 ice storm and a new arena for the [[Quebec Nordiques]]) being rejected outright. Though the vote on the budget was never scheduled, a budget is a confidence matter in its own right, so Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] asked the Governor General to dissolve Parliament.<ref name=\"macleans1\">{{cite web |last=Wells |first=Paul |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/05/05/not-feeling-the-love/ |title=The untold story of the 2011 election: Chapter 2 |website=Macleans.ca |date=2011-05-05 |accessdate=2012-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707021648/http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/05/05/not-feeling-the-love/ |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign the Conservatives portrayed the \"Liberal motion of non-confidence over the contempt-of-Parliament finding\" as mischief, instead of focusing on the economy and making constructive proposals for the budget. The Conservatives framed the election as a choice between a stable Conservative majority government or a Liberal coalition backed by the NDP and/or Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois.<ref name=\"macleans1\"/> The resulting election devastated two of the opposition parties who supported the contempt motion, with the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberals]] losing more than half their seats to drop to third place in the Commons for the first time, while the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] was nearly wiped out, with both their leaders also personally losing their ridings. The [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] gained enough seats to form a [[majority government]], while the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] won a record number of seats to form the [[Official Opposition (Canada)|Official Opposition]].\n\n===Province level===\nAt the provincial level, contempt operates in the legislative assemblies in much the same way that it does in the Senate or the House of Commons.\n\nWhile Section 18 of the Constitution Act, 1867 only grants parliamentary privilege (and therefore contempt powers) to the Senate and the House of Commons,<ref name=\":0\" /> court cases have since clarified that the provinces do have parliamentary privileges. The [[Supreme Court of Canada]], in ''[[New Brunswick Broadcasting Co v Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly)|New Brunswick Broadcasting Co. v. Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly)]]'', ruled that parliamentary privilege in both the provincial and the federal context is an unwritten convention of the [[Constitution of Canada|Canadian constitution]].<ref>{{cite court |litigants=New Brunswick Broadcasting Co. v. Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly) |reporter=1 SCR 319 |court=SCC |date=1993 |url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1993/1993canlii153/1993canlii153.html}}</ref>\n\nMore recent case law more clearly defined what parliamentary privileged means in the Canadian context, with the Supreme Court in ''[[Canada (House of Commons) v Vaid|Canada (House of Commons) v. Vaid]]'' defining parliamentary privilege in part as \"the sum of the privileges, immunities and powers enjoyed by the Senate, the House of Commons and provincial legislative assemblies.\"<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Canada (House of Commons) v. Vaid |reporter=1 SCR 667 |pinpoint=29 |court=SCC |date=2005 |url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/2005/2005scc30/2005scc30.html}}</ref> With case law establishing that provincial legislatures maintain parliamentary privileges, the door is open for a provincial legislature to use contempt of parliament powers.\n\nMost provinces have codified parliamentary privilege, at least in part,<ref>{{cite report|url=https://sencanada.ca/content/sen/Committee/412/rprd/rep/rep07jun15-e.pdf|title=A Matter of Privilege: Discussion Paper on Canadian Parliamentary Privilege in the 21st century|last=|first=|date=2015|publisher=Senate of Canada|issue=|doi=|volume=|page=32|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> such as in British Columbia's ''Legislative Assembly Privilege Act'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/jj32#sec8|title=Legislative Assembly Privilege Act, RSBC 1996, c 259, s 8|last=|first=|date=1996|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> or Manitoba's ''The Legislative Assembly Act'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/8gwr|title=The Legislative Assembly Act, CCSM c L110, ss, 40, 42|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> both of which touch on the powers of the legislatures to find people in contempt. [[Quebec]], the only [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]] province in Canada, has maintained its \"tradition of codification\"<ref name=\":1\" /> and has fully set out the privileges of their legislature, [[National Assembly of Quebec|The National Assembly]], in Division 1 of Chapter 3 of ''An Act Respecting the National Assembly,'' and maintains the \"power to protect its proceedings against all interference.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/53jcs#sec42|title=An Act Respecting the National Assembly, Chapter 3, Devision 1, Section 42|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Hong Kong==\n\nContempt of the Legislative Council is a criminal offence in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_ind.nsf/B505654FA2FD062B4825647A00339D10/64C13573F10A5859C825648300293C0E?OpenDocument |title=Cap 382 s 17 Contempts (LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL (POWERS AND PRIVILEGES) ORDINANCE) |website=Legislation.gov.hk |date=1997-06-30 |accessdate=2013-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\nContempt of Parliament consists of interference with [[parliamentary privilege]]<ref>Parliamentary privilege consists of freedom of speech on the floor of the House and in committee, freedom from arrest, regulating its membership and exclusive cognisance of internal affairs. Privilege extends to the publication of papers and reports by order of the House, including the official record [[Hansard]]. Freedom from arrest originally prevented the arrest (on criminal as well as civil grounds) of members, their goods and their staff.  The freedom from arrest of servants and goods were removed in the 18th century as the privilege was open to abuse, as was immunity from arrest for criminal acts. MPs today are only protected from arrest on civil grounds, for contempt of court. Regulation of composition extends to determining who is elected and whether they may take their seat. The result of elections is now ''de facto'' a matter for an Election Court composed of [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] judges, who issue a certificate to the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker]] in the case of elections where the result is disputed. The House also has exclusive right to determine whether members may take up their seat, including whether a member is eligible to take the relevant oath. Exclusive cognisance of internal affairs extends to the right to determine the oaths to be taken by members and who may take them (''Bradlaugh v Gossett''), the right to determine who may use House of Commons facilities and the exclusion of the jurisdiction of the courts as to alcohol sale offences within the Palace of Westminster.</ref> and of certain acts that obstruct the house and its members in their business.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/03/brexit-legal-advice-and-contempt-of-parliament-explainer|title=Brexit legal advice and threat of contempt of Parliament \u2013 explainer|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=3 December 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe same rules as apply to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] apply to the [[House of Lords]] ''[[mutatis mutandis]]'' (i.e. with the necessary modifications).\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], it has been alleged that arresting a member of Parliament in the course of carrying out his duties may constitute contempt of Parliament,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Allegation made by Michael Howard, a lawyer and former Home Secretary|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/nov/28/conservatives1 | location=London | work=The Guardian|first1=Nicholas|last1=Watt|first2=Andrew|last2=Sparrow|date=28 November 2008}}</ref> although immunity from criminal arrest was removed by the Parliamentary Privilege Acts of the 18th century.\n\nIt is further contempt to bribe or attempt to bribe any member (and for any member to accept or solicit a bribe), to disrupt the sittings of the House or a committee\u2014wherever it is sitting, to refuse to appear before a committee to testify, to refuse to answer any question put by a committee, to lie to a committee or to refuse to swear an oath (or make a solemn affirmation) when testifying, or to otherwise obstruct the business of the House.\n\nMPs accused of contempt of Parliament may be suspended or expelled.<ref name=Lyne>{{cite news |title=Contempt Drama Grips Parliament |author=Peter Lyne |newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor |date= March 26, 1964 |page=13 }}</ref>  They may also be committed to the [[Big Ben|clock tower of the Palace of Westminster]],<ref name=Lyne /> although this practice has not been used since [[Charles Bradlaugh]] was detained in 1880.  Strangers (those who are not members of the House) may be committed to prison during the life of the Parliament. The House of Lords has the power to fine as well as to order imprisonment for a term of years.\n\nOn 4 December 2018, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] was found in contempt of Parliament for the first time in history<ref name=\"Please back my deal Sky News\">\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://news.sky.com/story/mps-gear-up-for-marathon-five-day-brexit-deal-debate-11571280\n |title=Govt found in contempt of Parliament for first time in history over Brexit legal advice\n |website=Sky News|access-date=2018-12-04\n}}</ref> on a motion passed by MPs by 311 to 293 votes.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-12-04/division/15C96E04-84B4-4E2E-ADEA-64491F96C84A/Privilege(WithdrawalAgreementLegalAdvice)?outputType=Names\n |title=Division 273, Privilege (Withdrawal Agreement: Legal Advice) - Hansard\n |website=hansard.parliament.uk\n |access-date=2019-05-04\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/status/1069999732825735169|title=House of Commons votes 311 to 293 to approve the privilege motion, finding Ministers in contempt and ordering the immediate publication of the full legal advice on the #Brexit deal.pic.twitter.com/haXVmbH36s\n |last=Commons|first=UK House of\n |date=2018-12-04\n |website=@HouseofCommons\n |access-date=2018-12-04\n}}</ref> The vote was triggered by the government failing to lay before Parliament any legal advice on the proposed withdrawal agreement on the terms of the [[Brexit|UK's departure from the European Union]], after a [[Humble address#Address for a return|humble address for a return]] was unanimously agreed to by the House of Commons on 13 November. The government then agreed to publish the full legal advice<ref name=\"Please back my deal Sky News\" /> for [[Brexit]] that was given to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] during negotiations with the [[European Union]].  However, this advice was never published in full.\n\n==United States==\n{{main|Contempt of Congress}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contempt of court]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Politics of Australia|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Contempt Of Parliament}}\n[[Category:Political terminology in Australia]]\n[[Category:Political terminology in Canada]]\n[[Category:Political terms in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary procedure]]\n", "text_old": "{{use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\nIn countries with a [[parliamentary system of government]], '''contempt of Parliament''' is the offence of obstructing the [[legislature]] in the carrying out of its functions, or of hindering any [[legislator]] in the performance of their duties. The concept is common in countries with a parliamentary system in the [[Westminster system|Westminster model]], or which are derived from or influenced by the Westminster model. The offence is known by various other names in jurisdictions in which the legislature is not called \"[[Parliament]]\", most notably '''[[contempt of Congress]]''' in the United States. Actions that may constitute contempt of Parliament include:\n* deliberately misleading a house of the legislature, or a legislative [[committee]];\n* refusing to [[testify]] before, or to produce documents to, a house or committee; and\n* attempting to influence a member of the legislature by bribery or threats.\n\nIn some jurisdictions, a house of the legislature may declare any act to constitute contempt, and this is not subject to judicial review. In others, contempt of Parliament is defined by [[statute]]; while the legislature makes the initial decision of whether to punish for contempt, the person or organisation in contempt may appeal to the [[court]]s. Some jurisdictions consider contempt of Parliament to be a criminal offence.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.claruspress.ie/shop/contempt-of-parliament/|title=Contempt of Parliament|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==Australia==\n\n===Commonwealth level===\nIn the [[Commonwealth of Australia]], the ''Parliamentary Privileges Act 1987'' defines contempt of Parliament as:\n\n{{quote|Conduct (including the use of words)... [which] amounts, or is intended or likely to amount, to an improper interference with the free exercise by a House or committee of its authority or functions, or with the free performance by a member of the member's duties as a member.}}\n\nContempt decisions by the [[Australian House of Representatives|House of Representatives]] or the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] are subject to review by federal courts. This follows after the [[Browne\u2013Fitzpatrick privilege case, 1955|Browne\u2013Fitzpatrick privilege case]], in which Morgan, Fitzpatrick and Frank Browne were denied legal representation, subsequently convicted, and served 90 days each in jail for publishing an allegedly defamatory article against a member of Parliament.\n\nPunishments are limited under the Act to (for individuals) a [[fine (penalty)|fine]] of $5,000 and/or six months' imprisonment, or (for corporations) a fine of $25,000.\n\nIn the Senate, allegations of contempt are heard by the Privileges Committee, which decides whether or not contempt was committed, and if so, what punishment is to be imposed. In practice, there have been very few times when a hearing determined that anyone was in contempt, and on no occasions has anyone been punished beyond a warning, with an apology and/or other appropriate remedial action.\n\n===State level===\n{{expand section|date=January 2013}}\n\n==Canada==\n\n===Federal level===\n{{See also|Censure#Canada|Parliamentary privilege#In Canada}}\n\nThe power to find a person in contempt of Parliament stemmed from Section 18 of the ''[[Constitution Act, 1867]]'' in which \"The privileges, immunities, and powers to be held, enjoyed&nbsp;... shall not confer any privileges, immunities, or powers exceeding those at the passing of such Act held, enjoyed, and exercised by the Commons House of Parliament of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, and by the members thereof.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://laws.justice.gc.ca/en/const/2.html#anchorbo-ga:s_17|title=Constitution Acts, 1867|website=Laws.justice.gc.ca|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nRegarding the above-mentioned \"privileges\" there is an important difference between the \"individual parliamentary privileges\" and \"collective parliamentary privileges\". This difference is also important in any case of \"[[breach of privilege]]\" as it applies to [[Parliamentary privilege#In Canada|parliamentary privilege in Canada]].\n\n====Contempt citation cases for individuals====\nRarely has the [[Parliament of Canada|Canadian federal Parliament]] invoked its power to find an individual in contempt: There were \"contempt citation\" cases in 1913,<ref name=\"rare\">{{cite web |url=http://www.canada.com/topics/news/story.html?id=42920e1a-7f36-4dbc-902b-8b6cf9ae96bb |title=Examples of 'rare' contempt of Parliament cases |author=Canwest News Service |date=April 10, 2008 |publisher=CanWest MediaWorks Publications Inc |accessdate=21 March 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080411213208/http://www.canada.com/topics/news/story.html?id=42920e1a-7f36-4dbc-902b-8b6cf9ae96bb |archive-date=April 11, 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> 1976,<ref name=\"rare\"/> 2003,<ref name=\"rare\"/> 2008<ref name=\"rare\"/> and 2011.<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite news |title=PM on rulings: 'win some, lose some' |author= Laura Payton|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/09/pol-speaker-rulings.html |newspaper= [[CBC News]]|date=March 9, 2011 |accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe April 10, 2008 case involved [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]] deputy commissioner [[Barbara George (deputy commissioner)|Barbara George]] who was cited for contempt for deliberately misleading a [[parliamentary committee]] over an [[Giuliano Zaccardelli#Controversy over income trust file|income trust scandal]]. She was ultimately found in contempt but was not punished further than the [[Motion (legal)|motion]] itself.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/story/2008/04/10/rcmp-contempt.html|title=RCMP deputy commissioner found in contempt of Parliament|website=Cbc.ca|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe March 2011 contempt citation case involved [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative]] MP [[Bev Oda]].<ref name=\"PM\"/> While she was found to be ''[[prima facie]]'' in contempt by the [[Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada|Speaker]], Oda was not formally held in contempt because Parliament was dissolved before a vote could be held on the matter.<ref name=\"hook\">{{cite news |title=Oda off the hook |author=Mike De Souza |url= https://montrealgazette.com/business/hook/4507178/story.html|newspaper= [[Montreal Gazette]]|date= March 26, 2011|accessdate=26 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n====Contempt citation cases for governments====\nOn March 9, 2011, [[Speaker of the House of Commons of Canada|Speaker]] of the [[House of Commons of Canada]] [[Peter Milliken]] made two contempt of Parliament rulings: The first found that a [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservative Party]] cabinet minister, [[Bev Oda]], could possibly be in contempt of Parliament.<ref name=\"PM\"/> The second ruling found the [[Cabinet of Canada|Cabinet]] could possibly be in contempt of Parliament for not meeting Opposition members' requests for details of proposed bills and their cost estimates, an issue which had \"been dragging on since the fall of 2010\".<ref name=\"PM\"/><ref name=\"findings\"/> Milliken ruled that both matters must go to their responsible parliamentary committees and that the committee was required to report its findings to the Speaker by March 21, 2011 \u2013 one day before the proposal of the budget.\n\nConcerning the Speaker's first ruling, on March 18, 2011, Opposition members of the committee (who outnumbered the government members) said they still judged Oda to be in contempt of Parliament, despite her testimony that day,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/story/2011/03/18/pol-oda-privilege.html |title=MPs to return Monday on contempt debate |author=Laura Payton|date=18 March 2011|work= |publisher= [[CBC News]]|accessdate=21 March 2011}}</ref> but the committee process never proceeded far enough to make a finding as to whether Oda was in contempt.<ref name=\"hook\"/><ref name=\"findings\">{{cite news |url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/21/pol-privilege-contempt.html |title=MPs' report finds government in contempt |author= |date=21 March 2011|work= |publisher= [[CBC News]] |accessdate=24 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nConcerning the Speaker's second ruling, on March 21, 2011, the committee tabled a report<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://www2.parl.gc.ca/content/hoc/Committee/403/PROC/Reports/RP5047570/procrp27/procrp27-e.pdf |title=Question of Privilege Relating to the Failure of the Government To Fully Provide the Documents as Ordered by the House: Report of the Standing Committee on Procedure and House Affairs |accessdate=2011-04-26 |date=March 2011}}</ref> that found the Government of Canada in contempt of Parliament.<ref name=\"findings\"/> As such, a [[motion of no confidence]] was introduced in the House.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globaltvcalgary.com/personalities/Liberals+introduce+confidence+motion/4489986/story.html |title=Global News &#124; Latest & Current News - Weather, Sports & Health News |website=Globaltvcalgary.com |date= |accessdate=2013-08-31}}</ref> On March 25, 2011, [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|Members of Parliament]] voted on this motion, declaring a lack of confidence by a vote of 156 to 145 and [[2011 Canadian federal election|forcing an election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/story/2011/03/25/pol-defeat.html |title=MPs gather for historic vote |author=[[CBC News]] |publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]] |date=25 March 2011 |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref> The contempt finding is unique in Canadian history. In a wider context, it is the first time that any government in the 54-member [[Commonwealth of Nations]], either [[Commonwealth Realm]] or parliamentary republic, has been found in contempt of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://winnipeg.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110325/wpg_election_110325/20110325/?hub=WinnipegHome |title= Harper government topples on contempt motion, triggering May election|author= Bruce Cheadle|date=Mar 25, 2011 |work= |publisher= [[The Canadian Press]]; [[CTV news]]|accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Walkom: Yes, contempt of Parliament does matter |author= Thomas Walkom|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/politics/article/962022--walkom-yes-contempt-of-parliament-does-matter |newspaper=[[Toronto Star]] |date=March 25, 2011 |accessdate=25 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nEarlier that week, all three opposition parties had indicated that they would oppose the government's budget, with the NDP saying that the Conservatives' concessions did not go far enough, and the Bloc's earlier demands for $5 billion to their home province (including compensation for the 1998 ice storm and a new arena for the [[Quebec Nordiques]]) being rejected outright. Though the vote on the budget was never scheduled, a budget is a confidence matter in its own right, so Prime Minister [[Stephen Harper]] asked the Governor General to dissolve Parliament.<ref name=\"macleans1\">{{cite web |last=Wells |first=Paul |url=http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/05/05/not-feeling-the-love/ |title=The untold story of the 2011 election: Chapter 2 |website=Macleans.ca |date=2011-05-05 |accessdate=2012-03-19 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707021648/http://www2.macleans.ca/2011/05/05/not-feeling-the-love/ |archive-date=July 7, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign the Conservatives portrayed the \"Liberal motion of non-confidence over the contempt-of-Parliament finding\" as mischief, instead of focusing on the economy and making constructive proposals for the budget. The Conservatives framed the election as a choice between a stable Conservative majority government or a Liberal coalition backed by the NDP and/or Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois.<ref name=\"macleans1\"/> The resulting election devastated two of the opposition parties who supported the contempt motion, with the [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberals]] losing more than half their seats to drop to third place in the Commons for the first time, while the [[Bloc Qu\u00e9b\u00e9cois]] was nearly wiped out, with both their leaders also personally losing their ridings. The [[Conservative Party of Canada|Conservatives]] gained enough seats to form a [[majority government]], while the [[New Democratic Party of Canada|New Democratic Party]] won a record number of seats to form the [[Official Opposition (Canada)|Official Opposition]].\n\n===Province level===\nAt the provincial level, contempt operates in the legislative assemblies in much the same way that it does in the Senate or the House of Commons. \n\nWhile Section 18 of the Constitution Act, 1867 only grants parliamentary privilege (and therefor contempt powers) to the Senate and the House of Commons,<ref name=\":0\" /> court cases have since clarified that the provinces do have parliamentary privileges. The [[Supreme Court of Canada]], in ''[[New Brunswick Broadcasting Co v Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly)|New Brunswick Broadcasting Co. v. Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly)]]'', ruled that parliamentary privilege in both the provincial and the federal context is an unwritten convention of the [[Constitution of Canada|Canadian constitution]].<ref>{{cite court |litigants=New Brunswick Broadcasting Co. v. Nova Scotia (Speaker of the House of Assembly) |reporter=1 SCR 319 |court=SCC |date=1993 |url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/1993/1993canlii153/1993canlii153.html}}</ref> \n\nMore recent case law more clearly defined what parliamentary privileged means in the Canadian context, with the Supreme Court in ''[[Canada (House of Commons) v Vaid|Canada (House of Commons) v. Vaid]]'' defining parliamentary privilege in part as \"the sum of the privileges, immunities and powers enjoyed by the Senate, the House of Commons and provincial legislative assemblies.\"<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Canada (House of Commons) v. Vaid |reporter=1 SCR 667 |pinpoint=29 |court=SCC |date=2005 |url=https://www.canlii.org/en/ca/scc/doc/2005/2005scc30/2005scc30.html}}</ref> With case law establishing that provincial legislatures maintain parliamentary privileges, the door is open for a provincial legislature to use contempt of parliament powers.\n\nMost provinces have codified parliamentary privilege, at least in part,<ref>{{cite report|url=https://sencanada.ca/content/sen/Committee/412/rprd/rep/rep07jun15-e.pdf|title=A Matter of Privilege: Discussion Paper on Canadian Parliamentary Privilege in the 21st century|last=|first=|date=2015|publisher=Senate of Canada|issue=|doi=|volume=|page=32|pmid=|access-date=}}</ref> such as in British Columbia's ''Legislative Assembly Privilege Act'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/jj32#sec8|title=Legislative Assembly Privilege Act, RSBC 1996, c 259, s 8|last=|first=|date=1996|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> or Manitoba's ''The Legislative Assembly Act'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/8gwr|title=The Legislative Assembly Act, CCSM c L110, ss, 40, 42|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> both of which touch on the powers of the legislatures to find people in contempt. [[Quebec]], the only [[Civil law (legal system)|civil law]] province in Canada, has maintained its \"tradition of codification\"<ref name=\":1\" /> and has fully set out the privileges of their legislature, [[National Assembly of Quebec|The National Assembly]], in Division 1 of Chapter 3 of ''An Act Respecting the National Assembly,'' and maintains the \"power to protect its proceedings against all interference.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://canlii.ca/t/53jcs#sec42|title=An Act Respecting the National Assembly, Chapter 3, Devision 1, Section 42|last=|first=|date=2019|website=CanLII|access-date=}}{{dead link|date=January 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n==Hong Kong==\n\nContempt of the Legislative Council is a criminal offence in [[Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.hk/blis_ind.nsf/B505654FA2FD062B4825647A00339D10/64C13573F10A5859C825648300293C0E?OpenDocument |title=Cap 382 s 17 Contempts (LEGISLATIVE COUNCIL (POWERS AND PRIVILEGES) ORDINANCE) |website=Legislation.gov.hk |date=1997-06-30 |accessdate=2013-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==United Kingdom==\n\nContempt of Parliament consists of interference with [[parliamentary privilege]]<ref>Parliamentary privilege consists of freedom of speech on the floor of the House and in committee, freedom from arrest, regulating its membership and exclusive cognisance of internal affairs. Privilege extends to the publication of papers and reports by order of the House, including the official record [[Hansard]]. Freedom from arrest originally prevented the arrest (on criminal as well as civil grounds) of members, their goods and their staff.  The freedom from arrest of servants and goods were removed in the 18th century as the privilege was open to abuse, as was immunity from arrest for criminal acts. MPs today are only protected from arrest on civil grounds, for contempt of court. Regulation of composition extends to determining who is elected and whether they may take their seat. The result of elections is now ''de facto'' a matter for an Election Court composed of [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] judges, who issue a certificate to the [[Speaker of the House of Commons (United Kingdom)|Speaker]] in the case of elections where the result is disputed. The House also has exclusive right to determine whether members may take up their seat, including whether a member is eligible to take the relevant oath. Exclusive cognisance of internal affairs extends to the right to determine the oaths to be taken by members and who may take them (''Bradlaugh v Gossett''), the right to determine who may use House of Commons facilities and the exclusion of the jurisdiction of the courts as to alcohol sale offences within the Palace of Westminster.</ref> and of certain acts that obstruct the house and its members in their business.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/dec/03/brexit-legal-advice-and-contempt-of-parliament-explainer|title=Brexit legal advice and threat of contempt of Parliament \u2013 explainer|first=Peter|last=Walker|date=3 December 2018|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=3 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe same rules as apply to the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] apply to the [[House of Lords]] ''[[mutatis mutandis]]'' (i.e. with the necessary modifications).\n\nIn the [[United Kingdom]], it has been alleged that arresting a member of Parliament in the course of carrying out his duties may constitute contempt of Parliament,<ref>{{Cite news|title=Allegation made by Michael Howard, a lawyer and former Home Secretary|url= https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/nov/28/conservatives1 | location=London | work=The Guardian|first1=Nicholas|last1=Watt|first2=Andrew|last2=Sparrow|date=28 November 2008}}</ref> although immunity from criminal arrest was removed by the Parliamentary Privilege Acts of the 18th century.\n\nIt is further contempt to bribe or attempt to bribe any member (and for any member to accept or solicit a bribe), to disrupt the sittings of the House or a committee\u2014wherever it is sitting, to refuse to appear before a committee to testify, to refuse to answer any question put by a committee, to lie to a committee or to refuse to swear an oath (or make a solemn affirmation) when testifying, or to otherwise obstruct the business of the House.\n\nMPs accused of contempt of Parliament may be suspended or expelled.<ref name=Lyne>{{cite news |title=Contempt Drama Grips Parliament |author=Peter Lyne |newspaper=The Christian Science Monitor |date= March 26, 1964 |page=13 }}</ref>  They may also be committed to the [[Big Ben|clock tower of the Palace of Westminster]],<ref name=Lyne /> although this practice has not been used since [[Charles Bradlaugh]] was detained in 1880.  Strangers (those who are not members of the House) may be committed to prison during the life of the Parliament. The House of Lords has the power to fine as well as to order imprisonment for a term of years.\n\nOn 4 December 2018, the [[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] was found in contempt of Parliament for the first time in history<ref name=\"Please back my deal Sky News\">\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://news.sky.com/story/mps-gear-up-for-marathon-five-day-brexit-deal-debate-11571280\n |title=Govt found in contempt of Parliament for first time in history over Brexit legal advice\n |website=Sky News|access-date=2018-12-04\n}}</ref> on a motion passed by MPs by 311 to 293 votes.<ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2018-12-04/division/15C96E04-84B4-4E2E-ADEA-64491F96C84A/Privilege(WithdrawalAgreementLegalAdvice)?outputType=Names\n |title=Division 273, Privilege (Withdrawal Agreement: Legal Advice) - Hansard\n |website=hansard.parliament.uk\n |access-date=2019-05-04\n}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite web\n |url=https://twitter.com/HouseofCommons/status/1069999732825735169|title=House of Commons votes 311 to 293 to approve the privilege motion, finding Ministers in contempt and ordering the immediate publication of the full legal advice on the #Brexit deal.pic.twitter.com/haXVmbH36s\n |last=Commons|first=UK House of\n |date=2018-12-04\n |website=@HouseofCommons\n |access-date=2018-12-04\n}}</ref> The vote was triggered by the government failing to lay before Parliament any legal advice on the proposed withdrawal agreement on the terms of the [[Brexit|UK's departure from the European Union]], after a [[Humble address#Address for a return|humble address for a return]] was unanimously agreed to by the House of Commons on 13 November. The government then agreed to publish the full legal advice<ref name=\"Please back my deal Sky News\" /> for [[Brexit]] that was given to the [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom|Prime Minister]] by the [[Attorney General for England and Wales|Attorney General]] during negotiations with the [[European Union]].  However, this advice was never published in full.\n\n==United States==\n{{main|Contempt of Congress}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[Contempt of court]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n{{Politics of Australia|state=autocollapse}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Contempt Of Parliament}}\n[[Category:Political terminology in Australia]]\n[[Category:Political terminology in Canada]]\n[[Category:Political terms in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Parliamentary procedure]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eProvince level:Typo/generalfixes, replaced: therefor \u2192 therefore", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Contempt_of_Parliament"}
{"title_page": "Amari Cooper", "text_new": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name         = Amari Cooper\n|image        = File:Amari Cooper, Michael Crabtree, Seth Roberts 2017.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|alt          = \n|caption      = Cooper with the Oakland Raiders in 2015\n|current_team = Dallas Cowboys \n|number       = 19\n|position     = [[Wide receiver]] \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1994|6|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Miami, Florida]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  = \n|height_ft    = 6\n|height_in    = 1\n|weight_lbs   = 225\n|high_school  = [[Miami Northwestern Senior High School|Miami Northwestern]]<br>([[Miami, Florida]])\n|college      = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n|draftyear    = 2015\n|draftround   = 1\n|draftpick    = 4\n|pastteams    = \n*[[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n*[[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013present)\n|status       = Active\n|highlights   = \n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2016 Pro Bowl|2015]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]], [[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]], [[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2015|2015]])\n* [[BCS National Championship Game|BCS national champion]] ([[2013 BCS National Championship Game|2012]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[SEC Championship Game|SEC champion]] ([[2012 SEC Championship Game|2012]], [[2014 SEC Championship Game|2014]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] finalist ([[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season#Heisman Trophy voting|2014]])\n* [[Biletnikoff Award]] (2014)\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2014 College Football All-America Team|2014]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2014 All-SEC football team|2014]])\n|statseason   = 2019\n|statweek     =\n|statlabel1   = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1   = 357\n|statlabel2   = [[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2   = 5,097\n|statlabel3   = [[Average|Receiving average]]\n|statvalue3   = 14.2\n|statlabel4   = [[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue4   = 33\n|nflnew       = amaricooper/2552487\n|pfr          = CoopAm00\n}}\n\n'''Amari Delshon Cooper''' (born June 17, 1994) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]] where he was the [[Biletnikoff Award]] winner as the nation's top receiver and a unanimous [[All-American]] in 2014. Widely considered the top wide receiver prospect of the [[2015 NFL Draft]], he was selected with the fourth overall pick by the [[Oakland Raiders]].\n\nAfter successful rookie and sophomore seasons that included back-to-back 1,000-yard campaigns and two [[Pro Bowl]] appearances, Cooper struggled in his third season with the Raiders, totaling just 680 yards. Mid-way through the [[2018 NFL season|2018 season]] he was traded to the Cowboys and his play began to flourish again, including a 217-yard performance, and as a result, was voted to the third Pro Bowl of his career.\n\n==Early years==\nCooper attended [[Miami Northwestern Senior High School]] in [[Miami, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/alabama/2014/09/26/bridgewater-impressed-with-prep-teammate-coopers-play-at-alabama/16268101/ |title=Bridgewater impressed with prep teammate Cooper's play at Alabama |last=Rankin |first=Duane |work=The Montgomery Advertiser |access-date=January 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> As a junior, he missed much of the season with an injury but still managed to be one of quarterback [[Teddy Bridgewater]]'s primary targets and had 16 catches for 175 yards with four scores. Cooper was dominant on the 7-on-7 circuit at various college campuses before his senior season. He had a show out performance at Alabama's summer camp,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/why-elite-receivers-from-south-fla-keep-ending-up-at-alabama |title=Why elite receivers from south Fla. keep ending up at Alabama |date=September 21, 2016 |website=USA Today High School Sports}}</ref> and that quickly led to an offer from [[Nick Saban]] and the Crimson Tide. In his final year, he hauled in 33 receptions for 722 yards and 6 [[touchdowns]]. He was a first team [[Florida High School Athletic Association|FHSAA]] 8A All-State selection, as well as the No. 4 player on [[The Orlando Sentinel]]\u2019s Florida Top 100.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alabama.247sports.com/Article/Road-to-Stardom-Amari-Cooper-31437959 |title=Road to Stardom: Amari Cooper |website=24/7 Sports}}</ref> He was also invited to play at the [[Under Armour All-America Game|2012 Under Armour All-America Game]], where he had a 75-yard touchdown grab and a 93-yard punt return for a score. In addition to being a standout in football, Cooper also starred in [[high school basketball|basketball]] and [[track and field|track]] at Miami Northwestern.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://yellowhammernews.com/sports/accolades-roll-amari-cooper-remains-quiet-humble-destined-greatness/ |title=As accolades roll in, Amari Cooper remains quiet, humble and destined for greatness - Yellowhammer News |last=Biles |first=Jonathan |date=December 12, 2014 |website=Yellow Hammer News}}</ref>\n\nCooper was a consensus four-star prospect. He was listed as the No. 45 in the Rivals100, and was considered the No. 6 [[wide receiver]] and No. 8 player in [[Florida]] by [[Rivals.com]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Amari-Cooper-116486 |title=Rivals.com}}</ref> [[ESPNU]] listed him as the nation's No. 7 wideout and No. 46 overall prospect in the ESPNU 150 while ranking 25th in the ESPNU Southeast Top 100 and No. 12 in Florida.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2012/view/region/order/true/region/Southeast |title=ESPN Football Recruiting - Player Rankings - ESPN}}</ref> He was ranked as the No. 6 wide receiver and the No. 10 player in the state of Florida by [[247Sports.com]], while ranking him 55th in the Top247.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Season/2012-Football/RecruitRankings?InstitutionGroup=HighSchool |title=2012 Top Football Recruits}}</ref> Also, [[Scout.com]] rated him as the No. 12 pass catcher in the nation and 86th overall prospect.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=8&c=1&nid=5073853 |title=Amari Cooper, Oakland WR - Scout}}</ref> He chose Alabama over [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]], and [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]], among others. Cooper announced his verbal commitment to the [[University of Alabama]] on September 22, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rollbamaroll.com/2011/9/22/2443199/wr-amari-cooper-commits-to-alabama |title=WR Amari Cooper Commits to Alabama |date=September 22, 2011 |website=rollbamaroll.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===Freshman season===\nAs a freshman at Alabama, Cooper played in all 14 games, including starts in the final nine games. He led the team with 59 receptions for 1,000 yards and 11 [[touchdowns]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2012.html |title=2012 Alabama Crimson Tide Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/_/id/534458/amari-cooper |title=Amari Cooper}}</ref> The 11 touchdowns broke Alabama's 62-year-old record by [[Al Lary]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2013/08/amari_cooper_continues_his_str.html |title=Amari Cooper continues his string of exceptional scrimmages at Alabama |last=Kausler |first=Don |website=AL.com}}</ref> His receptions and receiving yards broke [[Julio Jones]]'s Alabama freshman records. In the SEC Championship, he had eight receptions for 128 yards and a touchdown in the 32\u201328 victory over [[2012 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-12-01-alabama.html |title=Georgia vs Alabama Box Score, December 1, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Alabama's [[2013 BCS National Championship Game]] 42\u201314 victory over [[2012 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]], Cooper led all Alabama receivers with 105 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-01-07-alabama.html |title=BCS Championship - Notre Dame vs Alabama Box Score, January 7, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/07/sports/la-sp-sn-bcs-title-game-notre-dame-vs-alabama-live-updates-20130107 |title=Alabama crushes Notre Dame, 42-14, for second straight BCS title |last=Hiserman |first=Mike |last2=Dufresne |first2=Chris |date=January 7, 2013 |via=LA Times}}</ref> Cooper earned consensus Freshman [[All-American]] honors and was selected to the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] All-Freshman team by the league coaches.<ref>[http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20130727/SPORTS0401/307260028 Wide receiver/tight end preview, Alabama: Cooper a rare talent, tight end spot more uncertain for Tide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208174531/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20130727/SPORTS0401/307260028 |date=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore season===\nAs a sophomore in 2013, Cooper played in 12 games with seven starts, missing two games due to injury. He had 45 receptions for a team-high 736 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/amari-cooper-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Amari Cooper 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> He had his best game of the season against [[2013 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the [[Iron Bowl]], recording six receptions for 178 yards, including a school record 99-yard touchdown reception from quarterback [[AJ McCarron]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/auburnfootball/index.ssf/2013/12/what_happened_to_auburns_defen.html |title=What happened to Auburn's defense on AJ McCarron's 99-yard touchdown pass in Iron Bowl? |last=Marcello |first=Brandon |website=AL.com}}</ref> In the [[2014 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] against [[2013 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]], he had nine receptions for 121 yards in the 45\u201331 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-01-02-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl - Oklahoma vs Alabama Box Score, January 2, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\nAs a junior in 2014, Cooper set numerous single-season and career records for Alabama.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-crimson-tide-amari-cooper-receiving-records-yards-touchdowns-catches-120214 |title=Amari Cooper owns every major Alabama receiving record |website=FOX Sports |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> Against [[2014 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he broke Alabama's single game receiving yards record, finishing with 224.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400548357 |title=Alabama vs. Tennessee - Game Recap - October 25, 2014 - ESPN}}</ref> He later matched the record against [[2014 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400548323 |title=Auburn vs. Alabama - Game Recap - November 29, 2014 - ESPN}}</ref> For the season, Cooper had 124 receptions for 1,727 yards and 16 touchdowns, all school records. In addition, his 124 receptions were an SEC record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_wr_amari_cooper_breaks.html |title=Alabama WR Amari Cooper breaks single-season SEC receptions record |last=Champlin |first=Drew |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> He became Alabama's all-time leader in receptions (228), receiving yards (3,463), and receiving touchdowns (31).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/receiving.html |title=Alabama Crimson Tide Receiving |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/local/story/2014/nov/08/amari-cooper-sets-alabama-career-yards-receiving-r/272970/ |title=Amari Cooper  sets Alabama career yards receiving record |website=Times Free Press |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alabama.247sports.com/Article/Amari-Cooper-sets-career-touchdown-record-vs-Florida-31347785 |title=Cooper sets touchdown record vs. Florida |last=Potter |first=Charlie |date=September 20, 2014 |publisher=BamaOnLine |access-date=September 24, 2014}}</ref> Cooper was a finalist for the [[Heisman Trophy]], finishing third behind [[Marcus Mariota]] and [[Melvin Gordon]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_receiver_amari_cooper_1.html |title=Alabama receiver Amari Cooper falls short in Heisman Trophy voting in record-breaking season |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> He won the [[Biletnikoff Award]] that season and was also named a unanimous [[All-American]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabamas_amari_cooper_wins_bil.html |title=Alabama's Amari Cooper wins Biletnikoff Award for nation's top receiver |last=Champlin |first=Drew |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_wr_amari_cooper_makes.html |title=Alabama WR Amari Cooper makes unanimous All-American |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter his junior season, Cooper entered the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft2015/story/_/id/12136972/alabama-crimson-tide-safety-landon-collins-leave-early-nfl-draft |title=Cooper, Yeldon, Collins leaving Bama for draft |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |website=ESPN.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/01/amari_cooper_tj_yeldon_nfl_draft.html |title=Amari Cooper, T.J. Yeldon reportedly leaving Alabama for NFL draft |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===College career statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=2|Year !! rowspan=2|Team !! rowspan=2|GP !! colspan=7|Receiving\n|-\n! Rec !! Rec\u2013Yards !! Avg !! TD !! Long !! 100+ !! Avg/G\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] || [[2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 14 || 59 || 1,000 || 16.9 || 11 || 54 || 5 || 71.4\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] || [[2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 12 || 45 || 736 || 16.4 || 4 || 99 || 2 || 61.3\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] || [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 14 || 124 || 1,727 || 13.9 || 16 || 80 || 7 || 123.4\n|-\n! colspan=2|Total !! 40 !! 228 !! 3,463 !! 15.2 !! 31 !! 99 !! 14 !! 86.6\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nCooper was considered one of the best wide receivers in the 2015 draft class, together with [[Kevin White (American football)|Kevin White]]. In most [[mock draft]]s, he was projected to be a top 10 pick, with some having him as high as the fourth pick in the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"davis_mock\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/mock-drafts/charles-davis/245610 |title=Mock Draft 4.0: Williams falls to Redskins |last=Davis |first=Charles |date=April 15, 2015 |work=NFL.com |access-date=April 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"jeremiah_mock\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/mock-drafts/daniel-jeremiah/245602 |title=Mock draft 4.0: Bears look to future at QB |last=Jeremiah |first=Daniel |date=March 18, 2015 |work=NFL.com |access-date=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215e\n|       weight = 211\n|         dash = 4.42\n|    ten split = 1.61\n| twenty split = 2.63\n|      shuttle = 3.98\n|   cone drill = 6.71\n|     vertical = 33\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 31\u00bd\n|    hand span = 10\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/profiles/amari-cooper?id=2552487</ref><ref>http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=122519&draftyear=2015&genpos=wr</ref>\n}}\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\n====2015 season: Rookie year====\nThe [[Oakland Raiders]] selected Cooper in the first round with the fourth overall pick in the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_28024302/nfl-draft-raiders-take-receiver-amari-cooper-at |title=NFL Draft: Raiders take receiver Amari Cooper at No. 4 |last=McDonald |first=Jerry |date=April 30, 2015 |work=San Jose Mercury News |access-date=April 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft2015/story/_/id/12795910/amari-cooper-drafted-oakland-raiders-no-4-overall-pick |title=Raiders draft Amari Cooper at No. 4 |last=Williamson |first=Bill |date=April 30, 2015 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=April 30, 2015}}</ref>\nCooper was initially assigned the jersey number 19, but following the release of fellow receiver [[James Jones (wide receiver)|James Jones]], he switched to number 89. Cooper made his NFL debut for the Oakland Raiders on September 13, 2015. He hauled in 5 receptions for 47 yards in a 33\u201313 loss to the [[2015 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130rai.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Oakland Raiders - September 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In his second game against the [[2015 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], he had 109 yards receiving including his first touchdown on a 68-yard pass from [[Derek Carr]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200rai.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Oakland Raiders - September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3, he had a franchise rookie record eight receptions for 134 yards in a 27-20 win against the [[2015 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], becoming the first Raiders receiver with consecutive 100+ yard receiving games since [[Randy Moss]] in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270cle.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Cleveland Browns - September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/GAME-NOTES-Raiders-27-Browns-20/bc2f542e-fbbc-45e2-aa72-8c0eef3ca4d4 |title=GAME NOTES: Raiders 27 Browns 20 |date=September 27, 2015 |publisher=Raiders.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> Through three games, his 290 receiving yards was third in NFL history. On November 8, 2015, Cooper passed [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]]'s record for rookie receptions (43) in a 35-38 loss to the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/GAME-NOTES-Steelers-38-Raiders-35/2eda804a-2b52-47dd-b3df-bb21134d797a |title=GAME NOTES: Steelers 38 Raiders 35 |date=November 8, 2015 |publisher=Raiders.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2015, Cooper became the first Oakland Raider rookie in franchise history to reach the 1,000-yard mark and the only receiver in the club to reach that same mark since [[Randy Moss]], in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://oak.247sports.com/Bolt/Amari-Cooper-becomes-Raiders-first-1000-yard-WR-in-10-years-42180985 |title=Amari Cooper becomes Raiders' first 1,000-yard WR in 10 years |last=Warnemuende |first=Jeremy |date=December 20, 2015 |publisher=247Sports.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> His five 100+ yard receiving games and 72 receptions are also franchise rookie records.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/psl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=combined&year_min=1920&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=1&team_id=rai&pos%5B%5D=qb&pos%5B%5D=rb&pos%5B%5D=wr&pos%5B%5D=te&pos%5B%5D=e&pos%5B%5D=t&pos%5B%5D=g&pos%5B%5D=c&pos%5B%5D=ol&pos%5B%5D=dt&pos%5B%5D=de&pos%5B%5D=dl&pos%5B%5D=ilb&pos%5B%5D=olb&pos%5B%5D=lb&pos%5B%5D=cb&pos%5B%5D=s&pos%5B%5D=db&pos%5B%5D=k&pos%5B%5D=p&draft_year_min=1936&draft_year_max=2017&draft_slot_min=1&draft_slot_max=500&draft_pick_in_round=pick_overall&conference=any&draft_pos%5B%5D=qb&draft_pos%5B%5D=rb&draft_pos%5B%5D=wr&draft_pos%5B%5D=te&draft_pos%5B%5D=e&draft_pos%5B%5D=t&draft_pos%5B%5D=g&draft_pos%5B%5D=c&draft_pos%5B%5D=ol&draft_pos%5B%5D=dt&draft_pos%5B%5D=de&draft_pos%5B%5D=dl&draft_pos%5B%5D=ilb&draft_pos%5B%5D=olb&draft_pos%5B%5D=lb&draft_pos%5B%5D=cb&draft_pos%5B%5D=s&draft_pos%5B%5D=db&draft_pos%5B%5D=k&draft_pos%5B%5D=p&c1stat=rec&c1comp=gt&c1val=50&c5val=1.0&order_by=rec_yds |title=Rookie receiving, Raiders franchise history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> On December 22, 2015, Cooper was selected as an alternate for the [[2016 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]], alongside teammates [[Derek Carr]] and [[Latavius Murray]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/three-raiders-selected-2015-pro-bowl |title=Amari Cooper named as alternate in 2016 Pro Bowl |last=Bair |first=Scott |website=Comcast Sports Network |access-date=December 22, 2015}}</ref> he replaced [[Brandon Marshall]] and played.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2609968-amari-cooper-replaces-brandon-marshall-at-2016-nfl-pro-bowl |title=Amari Cooper Replaces Brandon Marshall at 2016 NFL Pro Bowl |last=Rapp |first=Timothy |date=January 21, 2016 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nCooper put together a solid second season in the NFL. In the season opener against the [[2016 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], he had six receptions for 137 yards in a 35\u201334 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110nor.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at New Orleans Saints - September 11th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 5, against the [[2016 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]], he had six receptions for 138 yards and a touchdown in a 34\u201331 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610090rai.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at Oakland Raiders - October 9th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 8, against the [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had his best game of the season with 12 receptions for 173 yards and a touchdown in a 30\u201324 overtime victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610300tam.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - October 30th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he had 83 receptions for 1,153 yards and five touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://raiderswire.usatoday.com/2017/05/22/raiders-wr-amari-cooper-has-been-historic-in-first-two-seasons/ |title=Raiders WR Amari Cooper has been historic in first two seasons |last=Engelage |first=Christopher |date=May 22, 2017 |website=USAToday.com}}</ref> Cooper was named to his second consecutive [[2017 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] on December 20, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000760503/article/nfl-announces-2017-pro-bowl-rosters |title=NFL announces 2017 Pro Bowl rosters |date=December 20, 2016 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He was also ranked 53rd by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000810432/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-53-Amari-Cooper |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 53 Amari Cooper |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n[[File:Montae Nicholson (36593715674).jpg|thumb|left|[[Montae Nicholson]] of the [[Washington Redskins]] makes an interception over Cooper]]\n[[File:Amari Cooper 2017.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Cooper in 2017]]\nIn the season opener against the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Cooper had only 5 receptions for 62 yards on 13 targets, though one was a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100oti.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 10th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> After having 33 yards in Week 2, Cooper had three consecutive games with less than 10 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Amari Cooper 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> However, on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', in a 31\u201330 victory over the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in Week 7, Cooper caught 11 passes for a then career-high 210 receiving yards and two touchdowns. His yardage was the most by any NFL player at that point in the 2017 season, the second most in franchise history, and the first 200+ yard game in franchise history since 1965.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000864314/article/raiders-amari-cooper-busts-out-of-slump-in-big-way |title=Amari Cooper busts out of slump in big way |last=Patra |first=Kevin |publisher=NFL |access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=R&team_id=rai&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=rec_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=175&c5val=1.0&order_by=rec_yds |title=Single-game receiving, Raiders franchise history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> With his stellar performance in Week 7, Cooper earned AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000866951/article/carson-wentz-amari-cooper-among-players-of-week |title=Carson Wentz, Amari Cooper among Players of Week |last=Lam |first=Quang M. |date=October 25, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> After a string of games without stellar yardage totals, Cooper had three receptions for 66 receiving yards and a 63-yard touchdown during a Week 16 19-10 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. In the season finale against the [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], Cooper caught three receptions for 115 yards and an 87-yard touchdown in the 30\u201310 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310sdg.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Los Angeles Chargers - December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> It was later revealed that he struggled throughout the latter half of the season from an ankle injury that hampered his play.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/derek-carr-on-amari-coopers-down-season-he-was-out-there-playing-on-one-foot/ |title=Derek Carr on Amari Cooper's down season: He 'was out there playing on one foot' |last=Wagner-McGough |first=Sean |publisher=CBSSports |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> Cooper finished the 2017 season recording career-lows with 48 receptions for 680 yards but did have a career-high seven receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2017 |title=Amari Cooper 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn April 22, 2018, the Raiders exercised the fifth-year option on Cooper's contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/04/22/report-raiders-to-exercise-amari-coopers-option/ |title=Report: Raiders to exercise Amari Cooper\u2019s option |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=April 22, 2018 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4 against the [[2018 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Cooper caught eight passes for 128 yards and a touchdown in a 45\u201342 overtime win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.apnews.com/b54ace9b0eeb4c599334007ddb27bfa9 |title=Raiders rally past Browns 45-42 in OT for 1st win for Gruden |last=Dubow |first=Josh |date=October 1, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> During Week 6 against the [[2018 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] in London, Cooper was knocked unconscious when he suffered a concussion. The Raiders went on to lose 27-3.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/sports/football/nfl-helmet-to-helmet-hits.html |title=Helmet-to-Helmet Hits in N.F.L. Haven\u2019t Diminished, but Penalty Flags Have |last=Pennington |first=Bill |date=October 15, 2018 |website=New York Times |access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\n====2018 season====\nOn October 22, 2018, Cooper was traded to the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in exchange for a first-round pick (27th overall, [[Johnathan Abram]]) in the [[2019 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25055195/oakland-raiders-trade-amari-cooper-dallas-cowboys |title=Oakland Raiders to trade Amari Cooper to Dallas Cowboys |last=Archer |first=Todd |date=October 22, 2018 |website=[[ESPN]] |access-date=October 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his first game with the Cowboys on November 5, Cooper led the team with five receptions for 58 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost to the [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] by a score of 28-14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/raiders-nfl/titans-top-cowboys-28-14-in-amari-coopers-dallas-debut-1520145/ |title=Titans top Cowboys 28-14 in Amari Cooper\u2019s Dallas debut |date=November 6, 2018 |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US |access-date=May 1, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On Thanksgiving Day, Cooper had eight receptions for 180 yards and two touchdowns, including a 90-yard touchdown catch in the third quarter as the Cowboys defeated the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] by a score of 31-23. He was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000993457/article/philip-rivers-amari-cooper-among-players-of-the-week |title=Philip Rivers, Amari Cooper among Players of the Week |date=November 28, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> During Week 14 against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Cooper had 10 catches for a career-high 217 yards and three touchdowns. His final touchdown was in overtime and it came off a deflection from [[Rasul Douglas]] as the Cowboys won 29-23. His 217 receiving yards were the most by one player for a single game in the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/7GJvv |title=Most receiving yards, single game, 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> For his performance, Cooper earned his second NFC Offensive Player of the Week award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000998979/article/derrick-henry-amari-cooper-among-nfl-players-of-the-week |title=Derrick Henry, Amari Cooper among NFL Players of the Week |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=December 12, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Cowboys finished atop the NFC East with a 10-6 record and were the #4-seed for the NFC Playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/index.htm |title=2018 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: Dallas Cowboys 24, Seattle Seahawks 22|Wild Card Round]] victory over the [[2018 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]], Cooper had seven receptions for 106 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901050dal.htm |title=Wild Card - Seattle Seahawks at Dallas Cowboys - January 5th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: Los Angeles Rams 30, Dallas Cowboys 22|Divisional Round]] loss to the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams]], he had six receptions for 65 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901120ram.htm |title=Divisional Round - Dallas Cowboys at Los Angeles Rams - January 12th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> On January 21, 2019, Cooper was added to the NFC Pro Bowl roster as an injury replacement for [[New Orleans Saints]] wide receiver [[Michael Thomas (wide receiver, born 1993)|Michael Thomas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dallascowboys.com/news/cooper-prescott-added-to-nfc-pro-bowl-roster?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Cooper, Prescott Added to NFC Pro Bowl Roster |last=Eatman |first=Nick |website=Dallas Cowboys |language=en-US |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> In 15 games between the Raiders and Cowboys during the 2018 season, Cooper accumulated 75 receptions, 1,005 yards and 7 touchdown receptions.\n\n====2019 season====\nOn July 1, 2019, Cooper stated, \"I think the change of scenery was really necessary, I really, honestly, don\u2019t think if I would\u2019ve stayed with the Raiders last season that I would\u2019ve been able to flourish and reach some heights that I was able to reach as a Cowboy. So, it was definitely necessary.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2019/7/1/20677304/amari-cooper-in-order-to-flourish-in-nfl-i-needed-to-be-gone-from-oakland |title=Amari Cooper: In order to \u2018flourish\u2019 in NFL \u2018I needed to be gone\u2019 from Oakland |last=Damien |first=Levi |date=July 1, 2019 |website=www.silverandblackpride.com |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the season-opener against the [[2019 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Cooper caught six passes for 106 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys won by a score of 35\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128007 |title=Prescott lightens Elliott's load as Cowboys top Giants 35\u201317 |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2019 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]], he caught six passes for 88 yards and two touchdowns as the Cowboys won 31\u20136.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127921 |title=Prescott, Cowboys get out of funk, ease past Dolphins 31-6 |date=September 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 5, Cooper caught 11 passes for a career-high 226 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost to the [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] by a score of 34\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128029 |title=Rodgers, Packers rule at home of Cowboys again in 34-24 win |date=October 6, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 6, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 6 on the road against the [[2019 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Cooper caught one pass for three yards before leaving the game with a thigh injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27839675/cowboys-wr-amari-cooper-leaves-vs-jets-quad-injury |title=Cowboys WR Cooper ruled out with quad injury |date=October 13, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The Cowboys went on to lose 22\u201324. In the next game against the [[2019 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], he caught five passes for 106 yards in the Cowboys' 37\u201310 home victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127987 |title=Cowboys run over Eagles, take 1st in NFC East with 37-10 win |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> After a Week 8 bye, the Cowboys went on the road to face the New York Giants. Cooper caught four passes for 80 yards and a 45-yard fourth-quarter touchdown that sealed a 37\u201318 victory over their [[Cowboys-Giants rivalry|division rival]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128091 |title=Prescott throws for 3 TDs as Cowboys beat Giants again |date=November 3, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 3, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 10 against the [[2019 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], he caught 11 receptions for 147 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost by a score of 28\u201324. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128041 |title=Cook leads Vikings to 28-24 prime-time road win over Cowboys |date=November 10, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 10, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Three weeks later against the [[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', Cooper caught 6 passes for 83 yards and a touchdown in the 31\u201324 road loss. During the game, he reached 1,000 receiving yards on the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127871 |title=Mitchell Trubisky helps Bears beat Cowboys 31-24 |date=December 5, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 5, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nCooper finished the 2019 season with 79 receptions for a career-high 1,189 receiving yards and eight touchdowns in 16 games and starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Amari Cooper 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====2020 season====\nOn March 17, 2020, Cooper signed a five-year contract extension with the Cowboys worth $100 million, which featured $60 million guaranteed, $40 million at signing, and a $20 million injury designation that becomes fully guaranteed in 2022.<ref>{{cite news |author=Helman, David |title=Cooper Agrees To Terms on $100 Million Deal |url=https://www.dallascowboys.com/news/cooper-agrees-to-terms-on-100-million-deal |website=DallasCowboys.com |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n====Regular season====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost \n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] || [[2015 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| '''16''' || 15 || 72 || 1,070 || 14.9 || 68T || 6 || '''3''' || -3 || -1.0 || 2 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| '''16''' || 14 || '''83''' || 1,153 || 13.9 || 64T || 5 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || '''2''' || 0 \n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] || [[2017 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| 14 || 12 || 48 || 680 || 14.2 || 87T || 7 || 1 || 4 || 4.0 || 4 || 0 || 1 || 0 \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]] \n| 6 || 6 || 22 || 280 || 12.7 || 36 || 1 || 1 || 9 || 9.0 || 9 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| 9 || 9 || 53 || 725 || 13.7 || '''90T''' || 6 || 1 || '''11''' || '''11.0''' || '''11''' || 0 || '''2''' || '''2'''\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] || [[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 79 || '''1,189''' || '''15.1''' || 53T || '''8''' || 1 || 6 || 6.0 || 6 || 0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 76 !! 71 !! 357 !! 5,097 !! 14.2 !! 90T !! 33 !! 8 !! 27 !! 3.4 !! 11 !! 0 !! 6 !! 3 \n|}\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost \n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| 1 || 1 || 2 || 10 || 5.0 || 9 || 0 || '''1''' || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| '''2''' || '''2''' || '''13''' || '''171''' || '''13.2''' || '''34''' || '''1''' || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || '''1''' || 0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 3 !! 3 !! 15 !! 181 !! 12.1 !! 34 !! 1 !! 1 !! 0 !! 0.0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 1 !! 0\n|}\n\n===Records and achievements===\n====Raiders franchise records====\n\n* First rookie to reach the 1,000-yard receiving mark\n* Most receiving yards in a season by a rookie: 1,070\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly receiving leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121124170856/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cooper_amari00.html Alabama Crimson Tide bio]\n* [http://www.raiders.com/team/roster/Amari-Cooper/50d52821-5dbf-4347-9a09-06fd8ba66a73 Oakland Raiders bio]\n* [https://www.dallascowboys.com/team/players-roster/amari-cooper/ Dallas Cowboys bio]\n* [http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/_/id/2976499/amari-cooper ESPN.com bio]\n\n{{Dallas Cowboys roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n| list =\n{{Fred Biletnikoff Award}}\n{{2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{2014 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2015 NFL Draft}}\n{{RaidersFirstPick}}\n{{Raiders2015DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Amari}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Miami]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football wide receiver}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name         = Amari Cooper\n|image        = File:Amari Cooper, Michael Crabtree, Seth Roberts 2017.jpg\n|image_size   = \n|alt          = \n|caption      = Cooper with the Oakland Raiders in 2015\n|current_team = Dallas Cowboys \n|number       = 19\n|position     = [[Wide receiver]] \n|birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1994|6|17}}\n|birth_place  = [[Miami, Florida]]\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  = \n|height_ft    = 6\n|height_in    = 1\n|weight_lbs   = 225\n|high_school  = [[Miami Northwestern Senior High School|Miami Northwestern]]<br>([[Miami, Florida]])\n|college      = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n|draftyear    = 2015\n|draftround   = 1\n|draftpick    = 4\n|pastteams    = \n*[[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n*[[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|2018}}\u2013present)\n|status       = Active\n|highlights   = \n* 4\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[2016 Pro Bowl|2015]], [[2017 Pro Bowl|2016]], [[2019 Pro Bowl|2018]], [[2020 Pro Bowl|2019]])\n* [[PFWA All-Rookie Team]] ([[PFWA All-Rookie Team#2015|2015]])\n* [[BCS National Championship Game|BCS national champion]] ([[2013 BCS National Championship Game|2012]])\n* 2\u00d7 [[SEC Championship Game|SEC champion]] ([[2012 SEC Championship Game|2012]], [[2014 SEC Championship Game|2014]])\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] finalist ([[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season#Heisman Trophy voting|2014]])\n* [[Biletnikoff Award]] (2014)\n* Unanimous [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2014 College Football All-America Team|2014]])\n* First-team All-[[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] ([[2014 All-SEC football team|2014]])\n|statseason   = 2019\n|statweek     =\n|statlabel1   = [[Reception (American football)|Receptions]]\n|statvalue1   = 357\n|statlabel2   = [[Receiving yards]]\n|statvalue2   = 5,097\n|statlabel3   = [[Average|Receiving average]]\n|statvalue3   = 14.2\n|statlabel4   = [[Touchdown|Receiving touchdowns]]\n|statvalue4   = 33\n|nflnew       = amaricooper/2552487\n|pfr          = CoopAm00\n}}\n\n'''Amari Cooper''' (born June 17, 1994) is an [[American football]] [[wide receiver]] for the [[Dallas Cowboys]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). He played [[college football]] at the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]] where he was the [[Biletnikoff Award]] winner as the nation's top receiver and a unanimous [[All-American]] in 2014. Widely considered the top wide receiver prospect of the [[2015 NFL Draft]], he was selected with the fourth overall pick by the [[Oakland Raiders]].\n\nAfter successful rookie and sophomore seasons that included back-to-back 1,000-yard campaigns and two [[Pro Bowl]] appearances, Cooper struggled in his third season with the Raiders, totaling just 680 yards. Mid-way through the [[2018 NFL season|2018 season]] he was traded to the Cowboys and his play began to flourish again, including a 217-yard performance, and as a result, was voted to the third Pro Bowl of his career.\n\n==Early years==\nCooper attended [[Miami Northwestern Senior High School]] in [[Miami, Florida]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/story/sports/college/alabama/2014/09/26/bridgewater-impressed-with-prep-teammate-coopers-play-at-alabama/16268101/ |title=Bridgewater impressed with prep teammate Cooper's play at Alabama |last=Rankin |first=Duane |work=The Montgomery Advertiser |access-date=January 3, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> As a junior, he missed much of the season with an injury but still managed to be one of quarterback [[Teddy Bridgewater]]'s primary targets and had 16 catches for 175 yards with four scores. Cooper was dominant on the 7-on-7 circuit at various college campuses before his senior season. He had a show out performance at Alabama's summer camp,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://usatodayhss.com/2016/why-elite-receivers-from-south-fla-keep-ending-up-at-alabama |title=Why elite receivers from south Fla. keep ending up at Alabama |date=September 21, 2016 |website=USA Today High School Sports}}</ref> and that quickly led to an offer from [[Nick Saban]] and the Crimson Tide. In his final year, he hauled in 33 receptions for 722 yards and 6 [[touchdowns]]. He was a first team [[Florida High School Athletic Association|FHSAA]] 8A All-State selection, as well as the No. 4 player on [[The Orlando Sentinel]]\u2019s Florida Top 100.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alabama.247sports.com/Article/Road-to-Stardom-Amari-Cooper-31437959 |title=Road to Stardom: Amari Cooper |website=24/7 Sports}}</ref> He was also invited to play at the [[Under Armour All-America Game|2012 Under Armour All-America Game]], where he had a 75-yard touchdown grab and a 93-yard punt return for a score. In addition to being a standout in football, Cooper also starred in [[high school basketball|basketball]] and [[track and field|track]] at Miami Northwestern.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://yellowhammernews.com/sports/accolades-roll-amari-cooper-remains-quiet-humble-destined-greatness/ |title=As accolades roll in, Amari Cooper remains quiet, humble and destined for greatness - Yellowhammer News |last=Biles |first=Jonathan |date=December 12, 2014 |website=Yellow Hammer News}}</ref>\n\nCooper was a consensus four-star prospect. He was listed as the No. 45 in the Rivals100, and was considered the No. 6 [[wide receiver]] and No. 8 player in [[Florida]] by [[Rivals.com]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/footballrecruiting/football/recruiting/player-Amari-Cooper-116486 |title=Rivals.com}}</ref> [[ESPNU]] listed him as the nation's No. 7 wideout and No. 46 overall prospect in the ESPNU 150 while ranking 25th in the ESPNU Southeast Top 100 and No. 12 in Florida.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-sports/football/recruiting/playerrankings/_/class/2012/view/region/order/true/region/Southeast |title=ESPN Football Recruiting - Player Rankings - ESPN}}</ref> He was ranked as the No. 6 wide receiver and the No. 10 player in the state of Florida by [[247Sports.com]], while ranking him 55th in the Top247.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://247sports.com/Season/2012-Football/RecruitRankings?InstitutionGroup=HighSchool |title=2012 Top Football Recruits}}</ref> Also, [[Scout.com]] rated him as the No. 12 pass catcher in the nation and 86th overall prospect.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://recruiting.scout.com/a.z?s=73&p=8&c=1&nid=5073853 |title=Amari Cooper, Oakland WR - Scout}}</ref> He chose Alabama over [[Florida State Seminoles football|Florida State]], [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]], and [[Ohio State Buckeyes football|Ohio State]], among others. Cooper announced his verbal commitment to the [[University of Alabama]] on September 22, 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.rollbamaroll.com/2011/9/22/2443199/wr-amari-cooper-commits-to-alabama |title=WR Amari Cooper Commits to Alabama |date=September 22, 2011 |website=rollbamaroll.com}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===Freshman season===\nAs a freshman at Alabama, Cooper played in all 14 games, including starts in the final nine games. He led the team with 59 receptions for 1,000 yards and 11 [[touchdowns]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/2012.html |title=2012 Alabama Crimson Tide Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/player/_/id/534458/amari-cooper |title=Amari Cooper}}</ref> The 11 touchdowns broke Alabama's 62-year-old record by [[Al Lary]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2013/08/amari_cooper_continues_his_str.html |title=Amari Cooper continues his string of exceptional scrimmages at Alabama |last=Kausler |first=Don |website=AL.com}}</ref> His receptions and receiving yards broke [[Julio Jones]]'s Alabama freshman records. In the SEC Championship, he had eight receptions for 128 yards and a touchdown in the 32\u201328 victory over [[2012 Georgia Bulldogs football team|Georgia]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-12-01-alabama.html |title=Georgia vs Alabama Box Score, December 1, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Alabama's [[2013 BCS National Championship Game]] 42\u201314 victory over [[2012 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]], Cooper led all Alabama receivers with 105 yards and two touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2013-01-07-alabama.html |title=BCS Championship - Notre Dame vs Alabama Box Score, January 7, 2013 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2013/jan/07/sports/la-sp-sn-bcs-title-game-notre-dame-vs-alabama-live-updates-20130107 |title=Alabama crushes Notre Dame, 42-14, for second straight BCS title |last=Hiserman |first=Mike |last2=Dufresne |first2=Chris |date=January 7, 2013 |via=LA Times}}</ref> Cooper earned consensus Freshman [[All-American]] honors and was selected to the [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] All-Freshman team by the league coaches.<ref>[http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20130727/SPORTS0401/307260028 Wide receiver/tight end preview, Alabama: Cooper a rare talent, tight end spot more uncertain for Tide] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150208174531/http://www.montgomeryadvertiser.com/article/20130727/SPORTS0401/307260028 |date=February 8, 2015 }}</ref>\n\n===Sophomore season===\nAs a sophomore in 2013, Cooper played in 12 games with seven starts, missing two games due to injury. He had 45 receptions for a team-high 736 yards and four touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/amari-cooper-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Amari Cooper 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> He had his best game of the season against [[2013 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]] in the [[Iron Bowl]], recording six receptions for 178 yards, including a school record 99-yard touchdown reception from quarterback [[AJ McCarron]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/auburnfootball/index.ssf/2013/12/what_happened_to_auburns_defen.html |title=What happened to Auburn's defense on AJ McCarron's 99-yard touchdown pass in Iron Bowl? |last=Marcello |first=Brandon |website=AL.com}}</ref> In the [[2014 Sugar Bowl|Sugar Bowl]] against [[2013 Oklahoma Sooners football team|Oklahoma]], he had nine receptions for 121 yards in the 45\u201331 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2014-01-02-alabama.html |title=Sugar Bowl - Oklahoma vs Alabama Box Score, January 2, 2014 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Junior season===\nAs a junior in 2014, Cooper set numerous single-season and career records for Alabama.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-crimson-tide-amari-cooper-receiving-records-yards-touchdowns-catches-120214 |title=Amari Cooper owns every major Alabama receiving record |website=FOX Sports |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> Against [[2014 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he broke Alabama's single game receiving yards record, finishing with 224.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400548357 |title=Alabama vs. Tennessee - Game Recap - October 25, 2014 - ESPN}}</ref> He later matched the record against [[2014 Auburn Tigers football team|Auburn]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=400548323 |title=Auburn vs. Alabama - Game Recap - November 29, 2014 - ESPN}}</ref> For the season, Cooper had 124 receptions for 1,727 yards and 16 touchdowns, all school records. In addition, his 124 receptions were an SEC record.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_wr_amari_cooper_breaks.html |title=Alabama WR Amari Cooper breaks single-season SEC receptions record |last=Champlin |first=Drew |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> He became Alabama's all-time leader in receptions (228), receiving yards (3,463), and receiving touchdowns (31).<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/alabama/receiving.html |title=Alabama Crimson Tide Receiving |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/local/story/2014/nov/08/amari-cooper-sets-alabama-career-yards-receiving-r/272970/ |title=Amari Cooper  sets Alabama career yards receiving record |website=Times Free Press |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://alabama.247sports.com/Article/Amari-Cooper-sets-career-touchdown-record-vs-Florida-31347785 |title=Cooper sets touchdown record vs. Florida |last=Potter |first=Charlie |date=September 20, 2014 |publisher=BamaOnLine |access-date=September 24, 2014}}</ref> Cooper was a finalist for the [[Heisman Trophy]], finishing third behind [[Marcus Mariota]] and [[Melvin Gordon]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_receiver_amari_cooper_1.html |title=Alabama receiver Amari Cooper falls short in Heisman Trophy voting in record-breaking season |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> He won the [[Biletnikoff Award]] that season and was also named a unanimous [[All-American]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabamas_amari_cooper_wins_bil.html |title=Alabama's Amari Cooper wins Biletnikoff Award for nation's top receiver |last=Champlin |first=Drew |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2014/12/alabama_wr_amari_cooper_makes.html |title=Alabama WR Amari Cooper makes unanimous All-American |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter his junior season, Cooper entered the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft2015/story/_/id/12136972/alabama-crimson-tide-safety-landon-collins-leave-early-nfl-draft |title=Cooper, Yeldon, Collins leaving Bama for draft |last=Scarborough |first=Alex |website=ESPN.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.al.com/alabamafootball/index.ssf/2015/01/amari_cooper_tj_yeldon_nfl_draft.html |title=Amari Cooper, T.J. Yeldon reportedly leaving Alabama for NFL draft |last=Casagrande |first=Michael |website=AL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===College career statistics===\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=2|Year !! rowspan=2|Team !! rowspan=2|GP !! colspan=7|Receiving\n|-\n! Rec !! Rec\u2013Yards !! Avg !! TD !! Long !! 100+ !! Avg/G\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] || [[2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 14 || 59 || 1,000 || 16.9 || 11 || 54 || 5 || 71.4\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] || [[2013 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 12 || 45 || 736 || 16.4 || 4 || 99 || 2 || 61.3\n|-\n! [[2014 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2014]] || [[2014 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 14 || 124 || 1,727 || 13.9 || 16 || 80 || 7 || 123.4\n|-\n! colspan=2|Total !! 40 !! 228 !! 3,463 !! 15.2 !! 31 !! 99 !! 14 !! 86.6\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nCooper was considered one of the best wide receivers in the 2015 draft class, together with [[Kevin White (American football)|Kevin White]]. In most [[mock draft]]s, he was projected to be a top 10 pick, with some having him as high as the fourth pick in the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref name=\"davis_mock\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/mock-drafts/charles-davis/245610 |title=Mock Draft 4.0: Williams falls to Redskins |last=Davis |first=Charles |date=April 15, 2015 |work=NFL.com |access-date=April 16, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"jeremiah_mock\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/mock-drafts/daniel-jeremiah/245602 |title=Mock draft 4.0: Bears look to future at QB |last=Jeremiah |first=Daniel |date=March 18, 2015 |work=NFL.com |access-date=April 16, 2015}}</ref>\n{{nfl predraft\n|    height ft = 6\n|    height in = 0\u215e\n|       weight = 211\n|         dash = 4.42\n|    ten split = 1.61\n| twenty split = 2.63\n|      shuttle = 3.98\n|   cone drill = 6.71\n|     vertical = 33\n|     broad ft = 10\n|     broad in = 0\n|        bench = \n|    wonderlic = \n|     arm span = 31\u00bd\n|    hand span = 10\n|         note = All values from [[NFL Combine]]<ref>http://www.nfl.com/draft/2015/profiles/amari-cooper?id=2552487</ref><ref>http://www.draftscout.com/ratings/dsprofile.php?pyid=122519&draftyear=2015&genpos=wr</ref>\n}}\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\n====2015 season: Rookie year====\nThe [[Oakland Raiders]] selected Cooper in the first round with the fourth overall pick in the [[2015 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.mercurynews.com/raiders/ci_28024302/nfl-draft-raiders-take-receiver-amari-cooper-at |title=NFL Draft: Raiders take receiver Amari Cooper at No. 4 |last=McDonald |first=Jerry |date=April 30, 2015 |work=San Jose Mercury News |access-date=April 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/nfl/draft2015/story/_/id/12795910/amari-cooper-drafted-oakland-raiders-no-4-overall-pick |title=Raiders draft Amari Cooper at No. 4 |last=Williamson |first=Bill |date=April 30, 2015 |publisher=NFL.com |access-date=April 30, 2015}}</ref>\nCooper was initially assigned the jersey number 19, but following the release of fellow receiver [[James Jones (wide receiver)|James Jones]], he switched to number 89. Cooper made his NFL debut for the Oakland Raiders on September 13, 2015. He hauled in 5 receptions for 47 yards in a 33\u201313 loss to the [[2015 Cincinnati Bengals season|Cincinnati Bengals]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509130rai.htm |title=Cincinnati Bengals at Oakland Raiders - September 13th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In his second game against the [[2015 Baltimore Ravens season|Baltimore Ravens]], he had 109 yards receiving including his first touchdown on a 68-yard pass from [[Derek Carr]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509200rai.htm |title=Baltimore Ravens at Oakland Raiders - September 20th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 3, he had a franchise rookie record eight receptions for 134 yards in a 27-20 win against the [[2015 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], becoming the first Raiders receiver with consecutive 100+ yard receiving games since [[Randy Moss]] in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201509270cle.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Cleveland Browns - September 27th, 2015 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/GAME-NOTES-Raiders-27-Browns-20/bc2f542e-fbbc-45e2-aa72-8c0eef3ca4d4 |title=GAME NOTES: Raiders 27 Browns 20 |date=September 27, 2015 |publisher=Raiders.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> Through three games, his 290 receiving yards was third in NFL history. On November 8, 2015, Cooper passed [[Tim Brown (American football)|Tim Brown]]'s record for rookie receptions (43) in a 35-38 loss to the [[2015 Pittsburgh Steelers season|Pittsburgh Steelers]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/GAME-NOTES-Steelers-38-Raiders-35/2eda804a-2b52-47dd-b3df-bb21134d797a |title=GAME NOTES: Steelers 38 Raiders 35 |date=November 8, 2015 |publisher=Raiders.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 20, 2015, Cooper became the first Oakland Raider rookie in franchise history to reach the 1,000-yard mark and the only receiver in the club to reach that same mark since [[Randy Moss]], in 2005.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://oak.247sports.com/Bolt/Amari-Cooper-becomes-Raiders-first-1000-yard-WR-in-10-years-42180985 |title=Amari Cooper becomes Raiders' first 1,000-yard WR in 10 years |last=Warnemuende |first=Jeremy |date=December 20, 2015 |publisher=247Sports.com |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> His five 100+ yard receiving games and 72 receptions are also franchise rookie records.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/psl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=combined&year_min=1920&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=1&team_id=rai&pos%5B%5D=qb&pos%5B%5D=rb&pos%5B%5D=wr&pos%5B%5D=te&pos%5B%5D=e&pos%5B%5D=t&pos%5B%5D=g&pos%5B%5D=c&pos%5B%5D=ol&pos%5B%5D=dt&pos%5B%5D=de&pos%5B%5D=dl&pos%5B%5D=ilb&pos%5B%5D=olb&pos%5B%5D=lb&pos%5B%5D=cb&pos%5B%5D=s&pos%5B%5D=db&pos%5B%5D=k&pos%5B%5D=p&draft_year_min=1936&draft_year_max=2017&draft_slot_min=1&draft_slot_max=500&draft_pick_in_round=pick_overall&conference=any&draft_pos%5B%5D=qb&draft_pos%5B%5D=rb&draft_pos%5B%5D=wr&draft_pos%5B%5D=te&draft_pos%5B%5D=e&draft_pos%5B%5D=t&draft_pos%5B%5D=g&draft_pos%5B%5D=c&draft_pos%5B%5D=ol&draft_pos%5B%5D=dt&draft_pos%5B%5D=de&draft_pos%5B%5D=dl&draft_pos%5B%5D=ilb&draft_pos%5B%5D=olb&draft_pos%5B%5D=lb&draft_pos%5B%5D=cb&draft_pos%5B%5D=s&draft_pos%5B%5D=db&draft_pos%5B%5D=k&draft_pos%5B%5D=p&c1stat=rec&c1comp=gt&c1val=50&c5val=1.0&order_by=rec_yds |title=Rookie receiving, Raiders franchise history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> On December 22, 2015, Cooper was selected as an alternate for the [[2016 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]], alongside teammates [[Derek Carr]] and [[Latavius Murray]];<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.csnbayarea.com/raiders/three-raiders-selected-2015-pro-bowl |title=Amari Cooper named as alternate in 2016 Pro Bowl |last=Bair |first=Scott |website=Comcast Sports Network |access-date=December 22, 2015}}</ref> he replaced [[Brandon Marshall]] and played.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2609968-amari-cooper-replaces-brandon-marshall-at-2016-nfl-pro-bowl |title=Amari Cooper Replaces Brandon Marshall at 2016 NFL Pro Bowl |last=Rapp |first=Timothy |date=January 21, 2016 |website=Bleacher Report |access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref>\n\n====2016 season====\nCooper put together a solid second season in the NFL. In the season opener against the [[2016 New Orleans Saints season|New Orleans Saints]], he had six receptions for 137 yards in a 35\u201334 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201609110nor.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at New Orleans Saints - September 11th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 5, against the [[2016 San Diego Chargers season|San Diego Chargers]], he had six receptions for 138 yards and a touchdown in a 34\u201331 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610090rai.htm |title=San Diego Chargers at Oakland Raiders - October 9th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> In Week 8, against the [[2016 Tampa Bay Buccaneers season|Tampa Bay Buccaneers]], he had his best game of the season with 12 receptions for 173 yards and a touchdown in a 30\u201324 overtime victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201610300tam.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tampa Bay Buccaneers - October 30th, 2016 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> Overall, he had 83 receptions for 1,153 yards and five touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://raiderswire.usatoday.com/2017/05/22/raiders-wr-amari-cooper-has-been-historic-in-first-two-seasons/ |title=Raiders WR Amari Cooper has been historic in first two seasons |last=Engelage |first=Christopher |date=May 22, 2017 |website=USAToday.com}}</ref> Cooper was named to his second consecutive [[2017 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] on December 20, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000760503/article/nfl-announces-2017-pro-bowl-rosters |title=NFL announces 2017 Pro Bowl rosters |date=December 20, 2016 |website=NFL.com}}</ref> He was also ranked 53rd by his peers on the [[NFL Top 100 Players of 2017]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/videos/nfl-top100-2017/0ap3000000810432/Top-100-Players-of-2017-No-53-Amari-Cooper |title='Top 100 Players of 2017': No. 53 Amari Cooper |website=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n====2017 season====\n[[File:Montae Nicholson (36593715674).jpg|thumb|left|[[Montae Nicholson]] of the [[Washington Redskins]] makes an interception over Cooper]]\n[[File:Amari Cooper 2017.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Cooper in 2017]]\nIn the season opener against the [[2017 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]], Cooper had only 5 receptions for 62 yards on 13 targets, though one was a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201709100oti.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Tennessee Titans - September 10th, 2017 |website=[[Pro-Football-Reference.com]] |access-date=October 6, 2017}}</ref> After having 33 yards in Week 2, Cooper had three consecutive games with less than 10 receiving yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2017/ |title=Amari Cooper 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> However, on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', in a 31\u201330 victory over the [[2017 Kansas City Chiefs season|Kansas City Chiefs]] in Week 7, Cooper caught 11 passes for a then career-high 210 receiving yards and two touchdowns. His yardage was the most by any NFL player at that point in the 2017 season, the second most in franchise history, and the first 200+ yard game in franchise history since 1965.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000864314/article/raiders-amari-cooper-busts-out-of-slump-in-big-way |title=Amari Cooper busts out of slump in big way |last=Patra |first=Kevin |publisher=NFL |access-date=October 19, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/play-index/pgl_finder.cgi?request=1&match=game&year_min=1950&year_max=2017&season_start=1&season_end=-1&pos=0&game_type=R&team_id=rai&career_game_num_min=1&career_game_num_max=400&game_num_min=0&game_num_max=99&week_num_min=0&week_num_max=99&c1stat=rec_yds&c1comp=gt&c1val=175&c5val=1.0&order_by=rec_yds |title=Single-game receiving, Raiders franchise history |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com}}</ref> With his stellar performance in Week 7, Cooper earned AFC Offensive Player of the Week.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000866951/article/carson-wentz-amari-cooper-among-players-of-week |title=Carson Wentz, Amari Cooper among Players of Week |last=Lam |first=Quang M. |date=October 25, 2017 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> After a string of games without stellar yardage totals, Cooper had three receptions for 66 receiving yards and a 63-yard touchdown during a Week 16 19-10 loss to the [[2017 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]]. In the season finale against the [[2017 Los Angeles Chargers season|Los Angeles Chargers]], Cooper caught three receptions for 115 yards and an 87-yard touchdown in the 30\u201310 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201712310sdg.htm |title=Oakland Raiders at Los Angeles Chargers - December 31st, 2017 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref> It was later revealed that he struggled throughout the latter half of the season from an ankle injury that hampered his play.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/nfl/news/derek-carr-on-amari-coopers-down-season-he-was-out-there-playing-on-one-foot/ |title=Derek Carr on Amari Cooper's down season: He 'was out there playing on one foot' |last=Wagner-McGough |first=Sean |publisher=CBSSports |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> Cooper finished the 2017 season recording career-lows with 48 receptions for 680 yards but did have a career-high seven receiving touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2017 |title=Amari Cooper 2017 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 3, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====2018 season====\nOn April 22, 2018, the Raiders exercised the fifth-year option on Cooper's contract.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2018/04/22/report-raiders-to-exercise-amari-coopers-option/ |title=Report: Raiders to exercise Amari Cooper\u2019s option |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=April 22, 2018 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> In Week 4 against the [[2018 Cleveland Browns season|Cleveland Browns]], Cooper caught eight passes for 128 yards and a touchdown in a 45\u201342 overtime win.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.apnews.com/b54ace9b0eeb4c599334007ddb27bfa9 |title=Raiders rally past Browns 45-42 in OT for 1st win for Gruden |last=Dubow |first=Josh |date=October 1, 2018 |website=AP NEWS |access-date=October 10, 2018}}</ref> During Week 6 against the [[2018 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] in London, Cooper was knocked unconscious when he suffered a concussion. The Raiders went on to lose 27-3.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/14/sports/football/nfl-helmet-to-helmet-hits.html |title=Helmet-to-Helmet Hits in N.F.L. Haven\u2019t Diminished, but Penalty Flags Have |last=Pennington |first=Bill |date=October 15, 2018 |website=New York Times |access-date=October 15, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Dallas Cowboys===\n====2018 season====\nOn October 22, 2018, Cooper was traded to the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in exchange for a first-round pick (27th overall, [[Johnathan Abram]]) in the [[2019 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/25055195/oakland-raiders-trade-amari-cooper-dallas-cowboys |title=Oakland Raiders to trade Amari Cooper to Dallas Cowboys |last=Archer |first=Todd |date=October 22, 2018 |website=[[ESPN]] |access-date=October 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn his first game with the Cowboys on November 5, Cooper led the team with five receptions for 58 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost to the [[2018 Tennessee Titans season|Tennessee Titans]] by a score of 28-14.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reviewjournal.com/sports/raiders-nfl/titans-top-cowboys-28-14-in-amari-coopers-dallas-debut-1520145/ |title=Titans top Cowboys 28-14 in Amari Cooper\u2019s Dallas debut |date=November 6, 2018 |website=Las Vegas Review-Journal |language=en-US |access-date=May 1, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> On Thanksgiving Day, Cooper had eight receptions for 180 yards and two touchdowns, including a 90-yard touchdown catch in the third quarter as the Cowboys defeated the [[2018 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] by a score of 31-23. He was named the NFC Offensive Player of the Week for his performance.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000993457/article/philip-rivers-amari-cooper-among-players-of-the-week |title=Philip Rivers, Amari Cooper among Players of the Week |date=November 28, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref> During Week 14 against the [[2018 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], Cooper had 10 catches for a career-high 217 yards and three touchdowns. His final touchdown was in overtime and it came off a deflection from [[Rasul Douglas]] as the Cowboys won 29-23. His 217 receiving yards were the most by one player for a single game in the 2018 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pfref.com/tiny/7GJvv |title=Most receiving yards, single game, 2018 season |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=March 1, 2019}}</ref> For his performance, Cooper earned his second NFC Offensive Player of the Week award.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000998979/article/derrick-henry-amari-cooper-among-nfl-players-of-the-week |title=Derrick Henry, Amari Cooper among NFL Players of the Week |last=Knoblauch |first=Austin |date=December 12, 2018 |website=NFL.com |access-date=March 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Cowboys finished atop the NFC East with a 10-6 record and were the #4-seed for the NFC Playoffs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2018/index.htm |title=2018 NFL Standings & Team Stats |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: Dallas Cowboys 24, Seattle Seahawks 22|Wild Card Round]] victory over the [[2018 Seattle Seahawks|Seattle Seahawks]], Cooper had seven receptions for 106 yards.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901050dal.htm |title=Wild Card - Seattle Seahawks at Dallas Cowboys - January 5th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> In the [[2018\u201319 NFL playoffs#NFC: Los Angeles Rams 30, Dallas Cowboys 22|Divisional Round]] loss to the [[2018 Los Angeles Rams|Los Angeles Rams]], he had six receptions for 65 yards and a touchdown.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201901120ram.htm |title=Divisional Round - Dallas Cowboys at Los Angeles Rams - January 12th, 2019 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> On January 21, 2019, Cooper was added to the NFC Pro Bowl roster as an injury replacement for [[New Orleans Saints]] wide receiver [[Michael Thomas (wide receiver, born 1993)|Michael Thomas]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.dallascowboys.com/news/cooper-prescott-added-to-nfc-pro-bowl-roster?campaign=sf:fanshare:facebook |title=Cooper, Prescott Added to NFC Pro Bowl Roster |last=Eatman |first=Nick |website=Dallas Cowboys |language=en-US |access-date=January 22, 2019}}</ref> In 15 games between the Raiders and Cowboys during the 2018 season, Cooper accumulated 75 receptions, 1,005 yards and 7 touchdown receptions.\n\n====2019 season====\nOn July 1, 2019, Cooper stated, \"I think the change of scenery was really necessary, I really, honestly, don\u2019t think if I would\u2019ve stayed with the Raiders last season that I would\u2019ve been able to flourish and reach some heights that I was able to reach as a Cowboy. So, it was definitely necessary.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.silverandblackpride.com/2019/7/1/20677304/amari-cooper-in-order-to-flourish-in-nfl-i-needed-to-be-gone-from-oakland |title=Amari Cooper: In order to \u2018flourish\u2019 in NFL \u2018I needed to be gone\u2019 from Oakland |last=Damien |first=Levi |date=July 1, 2019 |website=www.silverandblackpride.com |access-date=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the season-opener against the [[2019 New York Giants season|New York Giants]], Cooper caught six passes for 106 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys won by a score of 35\u201317.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128007 |title=Prescott lightens Elliott's load as Cowboys top Giants 35\u201317 |date=September 8, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 8, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Two weeks later against the [[2019 Miami Dolphins|Miami Dolphins]], he caught six passes for 88 yards and two touchdowns as the Cowboys won 31\u20136.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127921 |title=Prescott, Cowboys get out of funk, ease past Dolphins 31-6 |date=September 22, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=September 22, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 5, Cooper caught 11 passes for a career-high 226 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost to the [[2019 Green Bay Packers season|Green Bay Packers]] by a score of 34\u201324.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128029 |title=Rodgers, Packers rule at home of Cowboys again in 34-24 win |date=October 6, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 6, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 6 on the road against the [[2019 New York Jets season|New York Jets]], Cooper caught one pass for three yards before leaving the game with a thigh injury.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/27839675/cowboys-wr-amari-cooper-leaves-vs-jets-quad-injury |title=Cowboys WR Cooper ruled out with quad injury |date=October 13, 2019 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> The Cowboys went on to lose 22\u201324. In the next game against the [[2019 Philadelphia Eagles season|Philadelphia Eagles]], he caught five passes for 106 yards in the Cowboys' 37\u201310 home victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127987 |title=Cowboys run over Eagles, take 1st in NFC East with 37-10 win |date=October 20, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=October 20, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> After a Week 8 bye, the Cowboys went on the road to face the New York Giants. Cooper caught four passes for 80 yards and a 45-yard fourth-quarter touchdown that sealed a 37\u201318 victory over their [[Cowboys-Giants rivalry|division rival]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128091 |title=Prescott throws for 3 TDs as Cowboys beat Giants again |date=November 3, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 3, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> During Week 10 against the [[2019 Minnesota Vikings season|Minnesota Vikings]], he caught 11 receptions for 147 yards and a touchdown as the Cowboys lost by a score of 28\u201324. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401128041 |title=Cook leads Vikings to 28-24 prime-time road win over Cowboys |date=November 10, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=November 10, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> Three weeks later against the [[2019 Chicago Bears season|Chicago Bears]] on ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'', Cooper caught 6 passes for 83 yards and a touchdown in the 31\u201324 road loss. During the game, he reached 1,000 receiving yards on the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/recap?gameId=401127871 |title=Mitchell Trubisky helps Bears beat Cowboys 31-24 |date=December 5, 2019 |website=www.espn.com |access-date=December 5, 2019 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nCooper finished the 2019 season with 79 receptions for a career-high 1,189 receiving yards and eight touchdowns in 16 games and starts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/players/C/CoopAm00/gamelog/2019/ |title=Amari Cooper 2019 Game Log |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====2020 season====\nOn March 17, 2020, Cooper signed a five-year contract extension with the Cowboys worth $100 million, which featured $60 million guaranteed, $40 million at signing, and a $20 million injury designation that becomes fully guaranteed in 2022.<ref>{{cite news |author=Helman, David |title=Cooper Agrees To Terms on $100 Million Deal |url=https://www.dallascowboys.com/news/cooper-agrees-to-terms-on-100-million-deal |website=DallasCowboys.com |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===NFL statistics===\n====Regular season====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost \n|-\n! [[2015 NFL season|2015]] || [[2015 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| '''16''' || 15 || 72 || 1,070 || 14.9 || 68T || 6 || '''3''' || -3 || -1.0 || 2 || 0 || 1 || 1\n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| '''16''' || 14 || '''83''' || 1,153 || 13.9 || 64T || 5 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || '''2''' || 0 \n|-\n! [[2017 NFL season|2017]] || [[2017 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| 14 || 12 || 48 || 680 || 14.2 || 87T || 7 || 1 || 4 || 4.0 || 4 || 0 || 1 || 0 \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| [[2018 NFL season|2018]] !! [[2018 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]] \n| 6 || 6 || 22 || 280 || 12.7 || 36 || 1 || 1 || 9 || 9.0 || 9 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n! [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| 9 || 9 || 53 || 725 || 13.7 || '''90T''' || 6 || 1 || '''11''' || '''11.0''' || '''11''' || 0 || '''2''' || '''2'''\n|-\n! [[2019 NFL season|2019]] || [[2019 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| '''16''' || '''16''' || 79 || '''1,189''' || '''15.1''' || 53T || '''8''' || 1 || 6 || 6.0 || 6 || 0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 76 !! 71 !! 357 !! 5,097 !! 14.2 !! 90T !! 33 !! 8 !! 27 !! 3.4 !! 11 !! 0 !! 6 !! 3 \n|}\n\n====Postseason====\n{| class= \"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"5\"| Receiving \n! colspan=\"5\"| Rushing \n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! Rec !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! Att !! Yds !! Avg !! Lng !! TD !! FUM !! Lost \n|-\n! [[2016 NFL season|2016]] || [[2016 Oakland Raiders season|OAK]]\n| 1 || 1 || 2 || 10 || 5.0 || 9 || 0 || '''1''' || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 \n|-\n! [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Dallas Cowboys season|DAL]]\n| '''2''' || '''2''' || '''13''' || '''171''' || '''13.2''' || '''34''' || '''1''' || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || '''1''' || 0 \n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 3 !! 3 !! 15 !! 181 !! 12.1 !! 34 !! 1 !! 1 !! 0 !! 0.0 !! 0 !! 0 !! 1 !! 0\n|}\n\n===Records and achievements===\n====Raiders franchise records====\n\n* First rookie to reach the 1,000-yard receiving mark\n* Most receiving yards in a season by a rookie: 1,070\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly receiving leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121124170856/http://www.rolltide.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/cooper_amari00.html Alabama Crimson Tide bio]\n* [http://www.raiders.com/team/roster/Amari-Cooper/50d52821-5dbf-4347-9a09-06fd8ba66a73 Oakland Raiders bio]\n* [https://www.dallascowboys.com/team/players-roster/amari-cooper/ Dallas Cowboys bio]\n* [http://espn.go.com/nfl/player/_/id/2976499/amari-cooper ESPN.com bio]\n\n{{Dallas Cowboys roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes\n| list =\n{{Fred Biletnikoff Award}}\n{{2012 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n{{2014 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{2015 NFL Draft}}\n{{RaidersFirstPick}}\n{{Raiders2015DraftPicks}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cooper, Amari}}\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American players of American football]]\n[[Category:American Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:American football wide receivers]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:National Conference Pro Bowl players]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Florida]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Miami]]\n[[Category:Unconferenced Pro Bowl players]]\n", "name_user": "2601:282:117f:c9d0:8005:c8b9:7765:2a63", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amari_Cooper"}
{"title_page": "Nanette Fabray", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2017}}\n{{more citations needed|date=February 2018}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Nanette Fabray\n| image         = Nanette Fabray 1963.JPG\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = Fabray in 1963\n| birthname     = Ruby Bernadette Nanette Theresa Fabares\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1920|10|27}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|2018|02|22|1920|10|27}}\n| death_place   = [[Palos Verdes, California]], U.S.\n| occupation    = {{hlist|actress|singer|dancer}}\n| yearsactive   = 1924\u20132018\n| spouse        = {{marriage|[[David Tebet]]|1947|1951|end=divorced}}<br />{{marriage|[[Ranald MacDougall]]|1957|1973|end=died}}\n| children      = 1\n| relatives     = [[Shelley Fabares]] (niece)\n}}\n\n'''Nanette Fabray''' (born '''Ruby Bernadette Nanette Theresa Fabares''';<ref name=\":0\" /> October 27, 1920 &nbsp;\u2013 February 22, 2018) was an American actress, singer, and dancer. She began her career performing in [[vaudeville]] as a child and became a musical-theatre actress during the 1940s and 1950s, acclaimed for her role in [[High Button Shoes]] (1947) and winning a [[Tony Award]] in 1949 for her performance in ''[[Love Life (musical)|Love Life]]''. In the mid-1950s, she served as [[Sid Caesar]]'s comedic partner on ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'', for which she won three [[Emmy Award]]s, as well as co-starring with [[Fred Astaire]] in the film musical ''[[The Band Wagon]]''. From 1979 to 1984, she appeared as Katherine Romano, the mother of lead character Ann Romano, on the TV series ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]''. She also appeared as the mother of Christine Armstrong (played by her niece Shelley Fabares) in the television series \"[[Coach (TV series)|Coach]].\"\n\nFabray overcame a significant [[Hearing loss|hearing impairment]] and was a long-time advocate for the rights of the deaf and hard-of-hearing. Her honors for representing the handicapped included the [[Distinguished Civilian Service Awards Board|President's Distinguished Service Award]] and the [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] Humanitarian Award.\n\n==Early life==\nFabray was born Ruby Bernadette Nanette Theresa Fabares on October 27, 1920, in San Diego, to Lily Agnes (McGovern), a housewife, and Raoul Bernard Fabares, a train conductor.<ref name=\"NYT 2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/02/23/obituaries/nanette-fabray-star-of-tv-and-stage-comedies-dies-at-97.html|title=Nanette Fabray, Star of TV and Stage Comedies, Dies at 97|first=Anita|last=Gates|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> She took to being known as Nanette for her first name after a beloved aunt from San Diego, whose name was also Nanette. Throughout life, she often went by the nickname Nan, and to a lesser extent, by close friends or relatives, sometimes Nanny-goat.<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray - Archive Interview  Part 1 of 6 - OOS|date=2008-03-25|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=Ki7NleR20-U|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> Her family resided in Los Angeles, and Fabray's mother was instrumental in getting her daughter involved in show business as a child. At a young age, she studied [[tap dance]] with, among others, [[Bill Robinson|Bill \"Bojangles\" Robinson]]. She made her professional stage debut as \"Miss New Years Eve 1923\" at the [[Million Dollar Theater]] at the age of three.<ref name=\"USAT 2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/tv/2018/02/23/nanette-fabray-star-stage-screen-and-tvs-one-day-time-dies-97/369461002/|title=Nanette Fabray, star of stage, screen and TV's 'One Day at a Time,' dies at 97|author=[[Associated Press]]|work=[[USA Today]]|publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|location=[[McLean, Virginia]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> She spent much of her childhood appearing in vaudeville productions as a dancer and singer under the name \u201cBaby Nan\u201d. She appeared with stars such as [[Ben Turpin]]. Raised by what would now likely be known as a stage mom, Fabray herself was not much interested in show business until later on, and never believed in pushing children into performing at a young age, instead wishing for them to be able to live out their childhoods as opposed to having to deal with adult concerns at a young age.<ref name=\":0\" /> Her early dance training, however, did lead her always to consider herself a tap dancer first and foremost.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1991-01-19/entertainment/ca-389_1_nanette-fabray|title=Hoofer at Heart, Funny Lady on the Stage :  Performance: Comedic roles gravitate to actress-tap dancer Nanette Fabray. She appears Sunday at Laguna Beach's Moulton Theatre.|last=HERMAN|first=JAN|date=1991-01-19|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-03-22|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Contrary to popular misinformation from an undying rumor, she was never a regular or reoccurring guest of the [[Our Gang]] series; she did however, appear as an extra one single time, a guest among many other children in a party scene.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nFabray's parents divorced when she was nine, but they continued living together for financial reasons. During the [[Great Depression]], her mother turned their home into a boarding house, which Fabray and her siblings helped run, Nanette\u2019s main job being ironing clothes.<ref name=\":0\" /> In her early teenage years, Fabray attended the [[Max Reinhardt]] School of the Theatre on a scholarship. She then attended [[Hollywood High School]], participating in the drama program with a favorite teacher, where she graduated in 1939.<ref name=\":0\" /> She beat out classmate [[Alexis Smith]] for the lead in the school play her senior year. Fabray entered [[Los Angeles City College|Los Angeles Junior College]] in the fall of 1939, but did not do well and withdrew a few months later.<ref name=\":0\" /> She had always had difficulty in school due to an undiagnosed hearing impairment, which made learning difficult. She eventually was diagnosed with a [[Conductive hearing loss|conductive]] hearing loss (due to congenital, progressive [[otosclerosis]]) in her twenties after an acting teacher encouraged her to get her hearing tested. Fabray said of the experience, \"It was a revelation to me. All these years I had thought I was stupid, but in reality I just had a hearing problem.\" Fabray gave many interviews over the years and much of the information known about her was revealed in these conversations. In 2004, she was interviewed<ref name=\":0\" /> for posterity in the oral history [[Archive of American Television|Archives of American Television]] as an Emmy TV legend.\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Pearl Bailey Nanette Fabray Arms and the Girl 1950.jpg|thumb|[[Pearl Bailey]] and Nanette Fabray in the Broadway musical ''Arms and the Girl'' (1950)]]\n\n===Theatre===\nAt the age of 19, Fabray made her feature film debut as one of [[Bette Davis]]'s ladies-in-waiting in ''[[The Private Lives of Elizabeth and Essex]]'' (1939). She appeared in two additional movies that year for [[Warner Bros.]], ''The Monroe Doctrine'' (short) and ''A Child Is Born'', but was not signed to a long-term studio contract. She next appeared in the stage production ''Meet the People'' in Los Angeles in 1940, which then toured the United States in 1940\u20131941. In the show, she sang the opera aria \"[[Caro nome]]\" from [[Giuseppe Verdi]]'s ''[[Rigoletto]]'' while tap dancing. During the show's New York run, Fabray was invited to perform the \"Caro nome\" number for a benefit at [[Madison Square Garden]] with [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] as the main speaker. [[Ed Sullivan]] was the [[master of ceremonies]] for the event and the famed host, reading a cue card, mispronounced her name as \"Nanette Fa-bare-ass.\" After this embarrassing ''faux pas'', the actress immediately legally changed the spelling of her name from Fabares to as close as possible match the proper pronunciation: Fabray.<ref name=\"archive\">\"{{cite web|url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/nanette-fabray|title=Interview with Nanette Fabray|date=August 12, 2004|first=Jennifer|last=Howard|work=[[Archive of American Television]]|publisher=[[Academy of Television Arts & Sciences Foundation]]|location=[[North Hollywood, Los Angeles]]|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> \n \n[[Artur Rodzi\u0144ski]], conductor of the [[New York Philharmonic]], saw Fabray's performance in ''Meet the People'' and offered to sponsor operatic vocal training for her at the [[Juilliard School]]. She studied opera at Juilliard with [[Lucia Dunham]] during the latter half of 1941 while performing in her first [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] musical, [[Cole Porter]]'s ''[[Let's Face It!]]'', with [[Danny Kaye]] and [[Eve Arden]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1959/04/03/82714582.html?action=click&contentCollection=Archives&module=LedeAsset&region=ArchiveBody&pgtype=article&pageNumber=27|title=Mrs. Lucia Dunham, Juilliard Teacher|work=[[The New York Times]]|publisher=[[The New York Times Company]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=April 3, 1959|page=27|url-access=subscription}}</ref> She decided that studying during the day and performing at night was too much for her and took away from her active social nightlife which she so enjoyed, and that she preferred performing in [[musical theatre]] over opera; thus she withdrew from the school after about five months.<ref name=\":0\" /> She became a successful musical-theatre actress in New York during the 1940s and early 1950s, starring in such productions as ''[[By Jupiter]]'' (1942), ''My Dear Public'' (1943), ''[[Jackpot (musical)|Jackpot]]'' (1944), ''[[Bloomer Girl]]'' (1946), ''[[High Button Shoes]]'' (1947), ''Arms and the Girl'' (1950), and ''[[Make a Wish (musical)|Make a Wish]]'' (1951). In 1949, she won the [[Tony Award for Best Actress in a Musical]] for her portrayal of Susan Cooper in the [[Kurt Weill]]/[[Alan Jay Lerner]] musical ''[[Love Life (musical)|Love Life]]''. She received a Tony nomination for her role as Nell Henderson in  ''[[Mr. President (musical)|Mr. President]]'' in 1963, after an 11-year absence from the New York stage.<ref name=\"archive\" /> Fabray continued to tour in musicals for many years, appearing in such shows as ''[[Wonderful Town]]'' and ''[[No, No, Nanette]]''.\n\n===Television and film===\n[[File:Nanette Fabray 1957.JPG|thumb|Fabray in 1957]]\nIn the mid-1940s, Fabray worked regularly for [[NBC]] on a variety of programs in the Los Angeles area. In the late 1940s and early 1950s, she made her first high-profile national television appearances performing on a number of variety programs such as ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'', ''[[Texaco Star Theatre]]'', and ''[[The Arthur Murray Party]]''.\n\nShe also appeared on ''[[Your Show of Shows]]'' as a guest star opposite [[Sid Caesar]]. She appeared as a regular on ''[[Caesar's Hour]]'' from 1954 to 1956, winning three Emmys. Fabray left the show after a misunderstanding when her business manager, unbeknownst to her, made unreasonable demands for her third-season contract. Fabray and Caesar did not reconcile until years later.<ref>{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray discusses working on \"Caesar's Hour\" - EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG|date=2015-07-22|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=pbvDwEyIo9E|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\nIn 1961, Fabray starred in 26 episodes of ''[[Westinghouse Playhouse]]'', a half-hour sitcom series that also was known as ''The Nanette Fabray Show'' or ''Yes, Yes Nanette''. The character was mainly loosely based on herself and her own life as a newly married couple with her husband and her new stepchildren.<ref>{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray - Archive Interview  Part 3 of 6|date=2008-03-25|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=bcJkEApJCxk|accessdate=2018-03-22}}</ref>\n\nFabray appeared as the mother of the main character on several television series such as ''[[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]]'', ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]'', and ''[[Coach (TV series)|Coach]]'', where she played mother to real-life niece [[Shelley Fabares]]. Like her aunt, Shelley Fabares also appeared on ''One Day at a Time.''\n\nFabray made 13 guest appearances on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''. She performed on multiple episodes of ''[[The Dean Martin Show]]'', ''[[The Hollywood Palace]]'', ''[[Kraft Music Hall (TV series)|Perry Como's Kraft Music Hall]]'', and ''[[The Andy Williams Show]]''. She was a panelist on 230 episodes of the long-running game show ''[[The Hollywood Squares]]'', as well as a mystery guest on ''[[What's My Line?]]'' and later a panelist on ''[[Match Game]]'' in 1973. Other recurring game show appearances by Fabray included participation in [[Password (game show)|Password]], [[I%27ve Got a Secret|I\u2019ve Got a Secret]], [[He Said, She Said (game show)|He Said, She Said]], and [[Celebrity Bowling]]. She also appeared on the game shows [[Pantomime Quiz|Stump the Stars]], [[Let's Make a Deal]], [[All Star Secrets]], and a television series families \"All Star special\" of [[Family Feud]] with fellow [[One Day at a Time (1975 TV series)|One Day at a Time]] cast members. \n\nShe appeared in guest-starring roles on ''[[Burke's Law (1963 TV series)|Burke's Law]]'', ''[[Love, American Style]]'', ''[[Maude (TV series)|Maude]]'', ''[[The Love Boat]]'', and ''[[Murder, She Wrote]]''. On the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] program ''Pioneers of Television: Sitcoms'', [[Mary Tyler Moore]] credited Fabray with inspiring her trademark comedic crying technique.\n\nIn 1953, Fabray played her best-known screen role as a [[Betty Comden]]-like playwright in the [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]] musical ''[[The Band Wagon]]'' with [[Fred Astaire]] and [[Jack Buchanan]]. The film in one scene featured Fabray, Astaire, and Buchanan performing the classic comedic musical number \"Triplets\", which was also included in ''[[That's Entertainment, Part II]]''. Fabray's additional film credits include ''[[The Happy Ending]]'' (1969), ''[[Harper Valley PTA (film)|Harper Valley PTA]]'' (1978), and ''[[Amy (1981 film)|Amy]]'' (1981).<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nFabray's most recent work was in 2007, when she appeared in ''The Damsel Dialogues'', an original revue by composer [[Dick DeBenedictis]], with direction/choreography by Miriam Nelson. The show, which was performed at the Whitefire Theatre in [[Sherman Oaks, California]], focused on women's issues with life, love, loss, and the workplace.\n\n==Personal life==\nFabray's first husband, [[David Tebet]], was in television marketing and talent, and later became a vice president of NBC.<ref name=\"EW 2018\">{{cite magazine|url=http://ew.com/theater/2018/02/23/nanette-fabray-dead-one-day-time-star-dies-97/|title=Nanette Fabray, Tony winner and star of original One Day at a Time, dies at 97|first=Maureen Lee|last=Lenker|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Meredith Corporation]]|location=[[New York City]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> According to Fabray, their marriage ended in divorce partially because of her depression, anxiety, and insecurities surrounding her worsening hearing loss. Her second husband was screenwriter [[Ranald MacDougall]], whose writing credits include ''[[Mildred Pierce (film)|Mildred Pierce]]'' and ''[[Cleopatra (1963 film)|Cleopatra]]'' and who, in the early 1970s, served as president of the [[Writers Guild of America]]. The couple were married from 1957 until his death in 1973. They had one son together: Jamie MacDougall.<ref name=\"NYT 2018\" /> \nShe was a resident of [[Pacific Palisades, California]], and was the aunt of singer/actress [[Shelley Fabares]]. Her niece's 1984 wedding to ''[[M*A*S*H (TV series)|M*A*S*H]]'' actor [[Mike Farrell]] was held at her home.<ref name=\"People - Fabares - 1991\">{{cite news|last1=Sanz|first1=Cynthia|title=Shelley Fabares Fell for a Former M*a*s*h-Er, Mike Farrell|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20114904,00.html|access-date=February 24, 2016|work=[[People (magazine)|People]]|publisher=[[Time Inc.]]|location=United States|date=April 15, 1991}}</ref> Longtime neighbors, Fabray was associated with [[Ronald Reagan]]'s campaign for the governorship of California in 1966.{{sfn|Critchlow|2013|page=191}}\n\nShe was hospitalized for almost two weeks after being knocked unconscious by a falling pipe backstage during a live broadcast of ''Caesar's Hour'' in 1955.<ref name=\"NYT 2018\" /> The audience in the studio heard her screams and Sid Caesar had at first been told she had been killed in the freak accident. Fabray suffered a serious concussion along with associated temporary vision impairment and [[Photosensitivity in humans|photosensitivity]]/photophobia. Later, she realized she had only avoided being directly impaled because of the position she happened to have been in at the time (bending over as opposed to standing up straight).<ref>{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray discusses an accident on the set of \"Caesar's Hour\" - EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG|date=2015-07-22|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=K25iRt42U4g|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> In 1978, during the filming of ''Harper Valley PTA'', Fabray suffered a second major concussion when she was knocked over, hitting her neck on the sidewalk and the back of her head on a rock. The accident was caused when a live elephant appearing in the film was spooked by a drunken civilian bystander, who had bypassed the blocked-off street on the set, and stampeded. Fabray suffered associated memory loss and visual issues such as [[nystagmus]], but still had to finish her scenes (namely a car chase) in the movie, for which filming had not yet wrapped. She had to be closely directed and coached, fed line-by-line, as she could not remember any of her lines or cues due to the concussion. She also had to be filmed only from specific angles to mask the obvious abnormal eye movements the concussion had temporarily caused.<ref>{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray Interview Part 5 of 6 - EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG|date=2011-09-23|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MobRBNXKHmE&t=9m31s|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Platforms==\n'''Hearing Impairment'''  A longtime champion of hearing awareness and support of the deaf, she sat on boards and spoke at many related functions. A forward-thinking proponent of [[Total Communication|total communication]] and teaching the deaf language and communication in any way possible, including [[American Sign Language]] and not just the [[oralism]] method of the time, Fabray was one of, if not the first, to use sign language on [live] television,<ref>{{Citation|last=FoundationINTERVIEWS|title=Nanette Fabray discusses doing sign language on \"The Carol Burnett Show\" - EMMYTVLEGENDS.ORG|date=2015-07-22|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=8HXYh5lx-1o|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> something which she continued to showcase on many programs on which she made appearances, including the ''[[The Carol Burnett Show|Carol Burnett Show]], [[Match Game|Match Game \u201873]]'', and ''[[I've Got a Secret|I\u2019ve Got a Secret]]''. She even contributed the story line to an entire 1982 episode<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tv.com/shows/one-day-at-a-time/hear-today-gone-tomorrow-26965/|title=One Day at a Time: Hear Today, Gone Tomorrow|last=TV.com|website=TV.com|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> of ''One Day at a Time'', which focused on hearing loss awareness and acceptance, treatment options, and sign language. Fabray appeared in a 1986 infomercial for hearing device and deafness support products for House Ear Institute.<ref>{{Citation|last=House Ear Institute|title=PI 6 Extra Sense Assistive Listening Devices for the Hearing Impaired    1985|date=2016-08-31|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=j7eHqWEH-Eo|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref> In 2001, she wrote to advice columnist [[Dear Abby]] to decry the loud [[background music]] played on television programs.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uexpress.com/dearabby/?uc_full_date=20010406|title=Letter to Dear Abby|work=Uexpress|publisher=[[Andrews McMeel Universal]]|location=United States|date=April 6, 2001|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> A founding member of the National Captioning Institute,<ref name=\":0\" /> she also was one of the first big names<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/Culture/video/march-23-1979-nanette-fabray-campaigns-closed-captions-53319221|title=Video: March 23, 1979: Nanette Fabray campaigns for closed captions on television|last=News|first=ABC|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> to bring awareness to the need for media closed-captioning.<ref>{{Citation|last=pannoni 8|title=November 16, 1986 commercials|date=2017-07-22|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=naKMgCbimtw&t=34m59s|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\n'''Widows\u2019 Rights''' After the passing of her second husband, Randy MacDougall, Fabray also started to learn about the tribulations associated with spousal death and began to bring awareness to the need for changes in the law for widows and widowers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/lifestyle/1984/04/19/fabray-with-flair/65584d06-c0e7-4724-b55d-322614764b0e/|title=Fabray, With Flair|date=1984-04-19|work=Washington Post|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en-US|issn=0190-8286}}</ref> She focused her later years on campaigning for widows\u2019 rights, particularly pertaining to women\u2019s inheritance laws, taxes, and asset protection.<ref>{{Citation|last=BLemack|title=Nanette Fabray 1991 Interview with Brad Lemack (Courtesy of RerunIt.com)|date=2018-02-24|url=https://youtube.com/watch?v=yXFMTWUBuQs&t=3m27s|accessdate=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nNanette Fabray died on February 22, 2018, at the Canterbury Nursing home in California at the age of 97 from natural causes.<ref name=\"McLellan 2018\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/obituaries/la-me-nanette-fabray-20180223-story.html|title=Actress Nanette Fabray, who won Tony and Emmy awards, dies at 97|first=Dennis|last=McLellan|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[tronc|Tronc, Inc.]]|location=[[Los Angeles]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Honors==\nA Tony and three-time Primetime Emmy award winner, Nanette Fabray has a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].<ref name=\"AJC 2018\">{{cite news|url=https://www.ajc.com/entertainment/celebrity-news/actress-nanette-fabray-tony-emmy-winning-star-stage-and-screen-dead/6Lc186k2ThxAX1teLiBcjL/|title=Actress Nanette Fabray, Tony, Emmy-winning star of stage and screen, dead at 97|first=Shelby Lin|last=Erdman|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|publisher=[[Cox Enterprises]]|agency=[[Cox Media Group]]|location=[[Dunwoody, Georgia]]|date=February 23, 2018|access-date=February 23, 2018}}</ref> In 1986, she received a [[Screen Actors Guild Life Achievement Award|Life Achievement]] award from the [[Screen Actors Guild]].\n\nShe won a [[Golden Apple Award|Golden Apple]] award from the [[Hollywood Women's Press Club|Hollywood Women\u2019s Press Club]] in 1960 along with [[Janet Leigh]] for being a Most Cooperative actress.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0264660/awards|title=Nanette Fabray|website=IMDb|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref>\n\nShe was awarded the President's Distinguished Service Award and the [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] Humanitarian Award for her long efforts on behalf of the deaf and hard-of-hearing.<ref name=\"AJC 2018\" />\n\n==Partial filmography ==\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n|-\n|1939\n|''[[The Private Lives of Elizabeth and Essex]]''\n|Mistress Margaret Radcliffe\n|-\n|1939\n|''[[A Child Is Born (film)|A Child Is Born]]''\n|Gladys Norton\n|-\n|1939\n|''The Monroe Doctrine''\n|Rosita De La Torre\n|-\n|1953\n|''[[The Band Wagon]]''\n|Lily Marton\n|-\n|1960\n|''[[The Subterraneans#Film version|The Subterraneans]]''\n|Society Woman\n|-\n|1969\n|''[[The Happy Ending]]''\n|Agnes\n|-\n|1970\n|''[[The Cockeyed Cowboys of Calico County]]''\n|Sadie\n|-\n|1978\n|''[[Harper Valley PTA (film)|Harper Valley PTA]]''\n|Alice Finley\n|-\n|1981\n|''[[Amy (1981 film)|Amy]]''\n|Malvina\n|-\n|1989\n|''The McFalls'' (aka ''Personal Exemptions'')\n|Mildred McFall\n|-\n|1994\n|''[[Teresa's Tattoo]]''\n|Martha Mae\n|-\n|2003\n|''[[Broadway: The Golden Age, by the Legends Who Were There]]''\n|Herself\n|}\n\n=== Television ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1954\u20131956\n| ''[[Caesar's Hour]]''\n| Herself\n|\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Laramie (TV series)|Laramie]]''\n| Essie Bright\n| Episode: \"Glory Road\"\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[Startime (TV series)|Startime]]''\n| Sally\n| Episode: \"The Nanette Fabray Show, or Help Me, Aphrodite\"\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Westinghouse Playhouse|The Nanette Fabray Show]]''\n| Nanette \"Nan\" McGovern\n| 26 episodes \n|-\n|rowspan=2|1966\n| ''[[Through the Looking-Glass#Dramatic adaptations|Alice Through the Looking Glass]]''\n| [[White Queen (Through the Looking-Glass)|The White Queen]]\n| TV Movie \n|-\n| ''[[Fame Is the Name of the Game]]''\n| Pat\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1967\u20131972\n| ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]''\n| Herself\n| 13 episodes\n|-\n|rowspan=2|1970\n| ''[[George M!]]''\n| Helen Costigan \"Nellie\" Cohan\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[But I Don't Want to Get Married!]]''\n| Mrs. Vale\n| TV Movie\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1972\n| ''Magic Carpet''\n| Virginia Wolfe\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| ''[[The Couple Takes a Wife]]''\n| Marion Randolph\n| TV Movie \n|-\n| ''[[The Mary Tyler Moore Show]]''\n| Dottie Richards\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Happy Anniversary and Goodbye]]''\n| Fay\n| TV Movie\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''[[Maude (TV 